4 // See https://llvm.org/LICENSE.txt for license information.

7 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
8 //
9 // Attributor: An inter procedural (abstract) "attribute" deduction framework.
10 //
11 // The Attributor framework is an inter procedural abstract analysis (fixpoint
12 // iteration analysis). The goal is to allow easy deduction of new attributes as
13 // well as information exchange between abstract attributes in-flight.
14 //
15 // The Attributor class is the driver and the link between the various abstract
16 // attributes. The Attributor will iterate until a fixpoint state is reached by
17 // all abstract attributes in-flight, or until it will enforce a pessimistic fix
18 // point because an iteration limit is reached.
19 //
20 // Abstract attributes, derived from the AbstractAttribute class, actually
21 // describe properties of the code. They can correspond to actual LLVM-IR
22 // attributes, or they can be more general, ultimately unrelated to LLVM-IR
23 // attributes. The latter is useful when an abstract attributes provides
24 // information to other abstract attributes in-flight but we might not want to
25 // manifest the information. The Attributor allows to query in-flight abstract
26 // attributes through the `Attributor::getAAFor` method (see the method
27 // description for an example). If the method is used by an abstract attribute
28 // P, and it results in an abstract attribute Q, the Attributor will
29 // automatically capture a potential dependence from Q to P. This dependence
30 // will cause P to be reevaluated whenever Q changes in the future.
31 //
32 // The Attributor will only reevaluate abstract attributes that might have
33 // changed since the last iteration. That means that the Attribute will not
34 // revisit all instructions/blocks/functions in the module but only query
35 // an update from a subset of the abstract attributes.
36 //
37 // The update method `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl` is implemented by the
38 // specific "abstract attribute" subclasses. The method is invoked whenever the
39 // currently assumed state (see the AbstractState class) might not be valid
40 // anymore. This can, for example, happen if the state was dependent on another
41 // abstract attribute that changed. In every invocation, the update method has
42 // to adjust the internal state of an abstract attribute to a point that is
43 // justifiable by the underlying IR and the current state of abstract attributes
44 // in-flight. Since the IR is given and assumed to be valid, the information
45 // derived from it can be assumed to hold. However, information derived from
46 // other abstract attributes is conditional on various things. If the justifying
47 // state changed, the `updateImpl` has to revisit the situation and potentially
48 // find another justification or limit the optimistic assumes made.
49 //
50 // Change is the key in this framework. Until a state of no-change, thus a
51 // fixpoint, is reached, the Attributor will query the abstract attributes
52 // in-flight to re-evaluate their state. If the (current) state is too
53 // optimistic, hence it cannot be justified anymore through other abstract
54 // attributes or the state of the IR, the state of the abstract attribute will
55 // have to change. Generally, we assume abstract attribute state to be a finite
56 // height lattice and the update function to be monotone. However, these
57 // conditions are not enforced because the iteration limit will guarantee
58 // termination. If an optimistic fixpoint is reached, or a pessimistic fix
59 // point is enforced after a timeout, the abstract attributes are tasked to
60 // manifest their result in the IR for passes to come.
61 //
62 // Attribute manifestation is not mandatory. If desired, there is support to
63 // generate a single or multiple LLVM-IR attributes already in the helper struct
64 // IRAttribute. In the simplest case, a subclass inherits from IRAttribute with
65 // a proper Attribute::AttrKind as template parameter. The Attributor
66 // manifestation framework will then create and place a new attribute if it is
67 // allowed to do so (based on the abstract state). Other use cases can be
68 // achieved by overloading AbstractAttribute or IRAttribute methods.
69 //
70 //
71 // The "mechanics" of adding a new "abstract attribute":
72 // - Define a class (transitively) inheriting from AbstractAttribute and one
73 // (which could be the same) that (transitively) inherits from AbstractState.
74 // For the latter, consider the already available BooleanState and
75 // {Inc,Dec,Bit}IntegerState if they fit your needs, e.g., you require only a
76 // number tracking or bit-encoding.
77 // - Implement all pure methods. Also use overloading if the attribute is not
78 // conforming with the "default" behavior: A (set of) LLVM-IR attribute(s) for
79 // an argument, call site argument, function return value, or function. See
80 // the class and method descriptions for more information on the two
81 // "Abstract" classes and their respective methods.
82 // - Register opportunities for the new abstract attribute in the
83 // `Attributor::identifyDefaultAbstractAttributes` method if it should be
84 // counted as a 'default' attribute.
85 // - Add sufficient tests.
86 // - Add a Statistics object for bookkeeping. If it is a simple (set of)
87 // attribute(s) manifested through the Attributor manifestation framework, see
88 // the bookkeeping function in Attributor.cpp.
89 // - If instructions with a certain opcode are interesting to the attribute, add
90 // that opcode to the switch in `Attributor::identifyAbstractAttributes`. This
91 // will make it possible to query all those instructions through the
92 // `InformationCache::getOpcodeInstMapForFunction` interface and eliminate the
93 // need to traverse the IR repeatedly.
94 //
95 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//

221 /// Return true if \p ToI is potentially reachable from \p FromI. The two
222 /// instructions do not need to be in the same function. \p GoBackwardsCB
223 /// can be provided to convey domain knowledge about the "lifespan" the user is
224 /// interested in. By default, the callers of \p FromI are checked as well to
225 /// determine if \p ToI can be reached. If the query is not interested in
226 /// callers beyond a certain point, e.g., a GPU kernel entry or the function
227 /// containing an alloca, the \p GoBackwardsCB should return false.
228 bool isPotentiallyReachable(
229  Attributor &A, const Instruction &FromI, const Instruction &ToI,
230  const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA,
231  std::function<bool(const Function &F)> GoBackwardsCB = nullptr);
232 
233 /// Same as above but it is sufficient to reach any instruction in \p ToFn.

235  Attributor &A, const Instruction &FromI, const Function &ToFn,
236  const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA,
237  std::function<bool(const Function &F)> GoBackwardsCB);

256 enum class DepClassTy {

263 /// The data structure for the nodes of a dependency graph
264 struct AADepGraphNode {
265 public:
266  virtual ~AADepGraphNode() = default;
267  using DepTy = PointerIntPair<AADepGraphNode *, 1>;
268 
269 protected:
270  /// Set of dependency graph nodes which should be updated if this one
271  /// is updated. The bit encodes if it is optional.
272  TinyPtrVector<DepTy> Deps;
273 
274  static AADepGraphNode *DepGetVal(DepTy &DT) { return DT.getPointer(); }
275  static AbstractAttribute *DepGetValAA(DepTy &DT) {
276  return cast<AbstractAttribute>(DT.getPointer());
277  }
278 
279  operator AbstractAttribute *() { return cast<AbstractAttribute>(this); }
280 
281 public:
282  using iterator =
283  mapped_iterator<TinyPtrVector<DepTy>::iterator, decltype(&DepGetVal)>;
284  using aaiterator =
285  mapped_iterator<TinyPtrVector<DepTy>::iterator, decltype(&DepGetValAA)>;
286 
287  aaiterator begin() { return aaiterator(Deps.begin(), &DepGetValAA); }
288  aaiterator end() { return aaiterator(Deps.end(), &DepGetValAA); }
289  iterator child_begin() { return iterator(Deps.begin(), &DepGetVal); }
290  iterator child_end() { return iterator(Deps.end(), &DepGetVal); }
291 
292  virtual void print(raw_ostream &OS) const { OS << "AADepNode Impl\n"; }
293  TinyPtrVector<DepTy> &getDeps() { return Deps; }
294 
295  friend struct Attributor;
296  friend struct AADepGraph;
297 };

299 /// The data structure for the dependency graph
300 ///
301 /// Note that in this graph if there is an edge from A to B (A -> B),
302 /// then it means that B depends on A, and when the state of A is
303 /// updated, node B should also be updated
304 struct AADepGraph {
305  AADepGraph() = default;
306  ~AADepGraph() = default;
307 
308  using DepTy = AADepGraphNode::DepTy;
309  static AADepGraphNode *DepGetVal(DepTy &DT) { return DT.getPointer(); }
310  using iterator =
311  mapped_iterator<TinyPtrVector<DepTy>::iterator, decltype(&DepGetVal)>;
312 
313  /// There is no root node for the dependency graph. But the SCCIterator
314  /// requires a single entry point, so we maintain a fake("synthetic") root
315  /// node that depends on every node.
316  AADepGraphNode SyntheticRoot;
317  AADepGraphNode *GetEntryNode() { return &SyntheticRoot; }
318 
319  iterator begin() { return SyntheticRoot.child_begin(); }
320  iterator end() { return SyntheticRoot.child_end(); }
321 
322  void viewGraph();
323 
324  /// Dump graph to file
325  void dumpGraph();
326 
327  /// Print dependency graph
328  void print();
329 };

331 /// Helper to describe and deal with positions in the LLVM-IR.
332 ///
333 /// A position in the IR is described by an anchor value and an "offset" that
334 /// could be the argument number, for call sites and arguments, or an indicator
335 /// of the "position kind". The kinds, specified in the Kind enum below, include
336 /// the locations in the attribute list, i.a., function scope and return value,
337 /// as well as a distinction between call sites and functions. Finally, there
338 /// are floating values that do not have a corresponding attribute list
339 /// position.
340 struct IRPosition {
341  // NOTE: In the future this definition can be changed to support recursive
342  // functions.
343  using CallBaseContext = CallBase;
344 
345  /// The positions we distinguish in the IR.
346  enum Kind : char {
347  IRP_INVALID, ///< An invalid position.
348  IRP_FLOAT, ///< A position that is not associated with a spot suitable
349  ///< for attributes. This could be any value or instruction.
350  IRP_RETURNED, ///< An attribute for the function return value.
351  IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED, ///< An attribute for a call site return value.
352  IRP_FUNCTION, ///< An attribute for a function (scope).
353  IRP_CALL_SITE, ///< An attribute for a call site (function scope).
354  IRP_ARGUMENT, ///< An attribute for a function argument.
355  IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT, ///< An attribute for a call site argument.
356  };
357 
358  /// Default constructor available to create invalid positions implicitly. All
359  /// other positions need to be created explicitly through the appropriate
360  /// static member function.
361  IRPosition() : Enc(nullptr, ENC_VALUE) { verify(); }
362 
363  /// Create a position describing the value of \p V.
364  static const IRPosition value(const Value &V,
365  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr) {
366  if (auto *Arg = dyn_cast<Argument>(&V))
367  return IRPosition::argument(*Arg, CBContext);
368  if (auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&V))
369  return IRPosition::callsite_returned(*CB);
370  return IRPosition(const_cast<Value &>(V), IRP_FLOAT, CBContext);
371  }
372 
373  /// Create a position describing the instruction \p I. This is different from
374  /// the value version because call sites are treated as intrusctions rather
375  /// than their return value in this function.
376  static const IRPosition inst(const Instruction &I,
377  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr) {
378  return IRPosition(const_cast<Instruction &>(I), IRP_FLOAT, CBContext);
379  }
380 
381  /// Create a position describing the function scope of \p F.
382  /// \p CBContext is used for call base specific analysis.
383  static const IRPosition function(const Function &F,
384  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr) {
385  return IRPosition(const_cast<Function &>(F), IRP_FUNCTION, CBContext);
386  }
387 
388  /// Create a position describing the returned value of \p F.
389  /// \p CBContext is used for call base specific analysis.
390  static const IRPosition returned(const Function &F,
391  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr) {
392  return IRPosition(const_cast<Function &>(F), IRP_RETURNED, CBContext);
393  }
394 
395  /// Create a position describing the argument \p Arg.
396  /// \p CBContext is used for call base specific analysis.
397  static const IRPosition argument(const Argument &Arg,
398  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr) {
399  return IRPosition(const_cast<Argument &>(Arg), IRP_ARGUMENT, CBContext);
400  }
401 
402  /// Create a position describing the function scope of \p CB.
403  static const IRPosition callsite_function(const CallBase &CB) {
404  return IRPosition(const_cast<CallBase &>(CB), IRP_CALL_SITE);
405  }
406 
407  /// Create a position describing the returned value of \p CB.
408  static const IRPosition callsite_returned(const CallBase &CB) {
409  return IRPosition(const_cast<CallBase &>(CB), IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED);
410  }
411 
412  /// Create a position describing the argument of \p CB at position \p ArgNo.
413  static const IRPosition callsite_argument(const CallBase &CB,
414  unsigned ArgNo) {
415  return IRPosition(const_cast<Use &>(CB.getArgOperandUse(ArgNo)),
416  IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT);
417  }
418 
419  /// Create a position describing the argument of \p ACS at position \p ArgNo.
420  static const IRPosition callsite_argument(AbstractCallSite ACS,
421  unsigned ArgNo) {
422  if (ACS.getNumArgOperands() <= ArgNo)
423  return IRPosition();
424  int CSArgNo = ACS.getCallArgOperandNo(ArgNo);
425  if (CSArgNo >= 0)
426  return IRPosition::callsite_argument(
427  cast<CallBase>(*ACS.getInstruction()), CSArgNo);
428  return IRPosition();
429  }
430 
431  /// Create a position with function scope matching the "context" of \p IRP.
432  /// If \p IRP is a call site (see isAnyCallSitePosition()) then the result
433  /// will be a call site position, otherwise the function position of the
434  /// associated function.
435  static const IRPosition
436  function_scope(const IRPosition &IRP,
437  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr) {
438  if (IRP.isAnyCallSitePosition()) {
439  return IRPosition::callsite_function(
440  cast<CallBase>(IRP.getAnchorValue()));
441  }
442  assert(IRP.getAssociatedFunction());
443  return IRPosition::function(*IRP.getAssociatedFunction(), CBContext);
444  }
445 
446  bool operator==(const IRPosition &RHS) const {
447  return Enc == RHS.Enc && RHS.CBContext == CBContext;
448  }
449  bool operator!=(const IRPosition &RHS) const { return !(*this == RHS); }
450 
451  /// Return the value this abstract attribute is anchored with.
452  ///
453  /// The anchor value might not be the associated value if the latter is not
454  /// sufficient to determine where arguments will be manifested. This is, so
455  /// far, only the case for call site arguments as the value is not sufficient
456  /// to pinpoint them. Instead, we can use the call site as an anchor.
457  Value &getAnchorValue() const {
458  switch (getEncodingBits()) {
459  case ENC_VALUE:
460  case ENC_RETURNED_VALUE:
461  case ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION:
462  return *getAsValuePtr();
463  case ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE:
464  return *(getAsUsePtr()->getUser());
465  default:
466  llvm_unreachable("Unkown encoding!");
467  };
468  }
469 
470  /// Return the associated function, if any.
471  Function *getAssociatedFunction() const {
472  if (auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue())) {
473  // We reuse the logic that associates callback calles to arguments of a
474  // call site here to identify the callback callee as the associated
475  // function.
476  if (Argument *Arg = getAssociatedArgument())
477  return Arg->getParent();
478  return CB->getCalledFunction();
479  }
480  return getAnchorScope();
481  }
482 
483  /// Return the associated argument, if any.
484  Argument *getAssociatedArgument() const;
485 
486  /// Return true if the position refers to a function interface, that is the
487  /// function scope, the function return, or an argument.
488  bool isFnInterfaceKind() const {
489  switch (getPositionKind()) {
490  case IRPosition::IRP_FUNCTION:
491  case IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED:
492  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
493  return true;
494  default:
495  return false;
496  }
497  }
498 
499  /// Return the Function surrounding the anchor value.
500  Function *getAnchorScope() const {
501  Value &V = getAnchorValue();
502  if (isa<Function>(V))
503  return &cast<Function>(V);
504  if (isa<Argument>(V))
505  return cast<Argument>(V).getParent();
506  if (isa<Instruction>(V))
507  return cast<Instruction>(V).getFunction();
508  return nullptr;
509  }
510 
511  /// Return the context instruction, if any.
512  Instruction *getCtxI() const {
513  Value &V = getAnchorValue();
514  if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(&V))
515  return I;
516  if (auto *Arg = dyn_cast<Argument>(&V))
517  if (!Arg->getParent()->isDeclaration())
518  return &Arg->getParent()->getEntryBlock().front();
519  if (auto *F = dyn_cast<Function>(&V))
520  if (!F->isDeclaration())
521  return &(F->getEntryBlock().front());
522  return nullptr;
523  }
524 
525  /// Return the value this abstract attribute is associated with.
526  Value &getAssociatedValue() const {
527  if (getCallSiteArgNo() < 0 || isa<Argument>(&getAnchorValue()))
528  return getAnchorValue();
529  assert(isa<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue()) && "Expected a call base!");
530  return *cast<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue())
531  ->getArgOperand(getCallSiteArgNo());
532  }
533 
534  /// Return the type this abstract attribute is associated with.
535  Type *getAssociatedType() const {
536  if (getPositionKind() == IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED)
537  return getAssociatedFunction()->getReturnType();
538  return getAssociatedValue().getType();
539  }
540 
541  /// Return the callee argument number of the associated value if it is an
542  /// argument or call site argument, otherwise a negative value. In contrast to
543  /// `getCallSiteArgNo` this method will always return the "argument number"
544  /// from the perspective of the callee. This may not the same as the call site
545  /// if this is a callback call.
546  int getCalleeArgNo() const {
547  return getArgNo(/* CallbackCalleeArgIfApplicable */ true);
548  }
549 
550  /// Return the call site argument number of the associated value if it is an
551  /// argument or call site argument, otherwise a negative value. In contrast to
552  /// `getCalleArgNo` this method will always return the "operand number" from
553  /// the perspective of the call site. This may not the same as the callee
554  /// perspective if this is a callback call.
555  int getCallSiteArgNo() const {
556  return getArgNo(/* CallbackCalleeArgIfApplicable */ false);
557  }
558 
559  /// Return the index in the attribute list for this position.
560  unsigned getAttrIdx() const {
561  switch (getPositionKind()) {
562  case IRPosition::IRP_INVALID:
563  case IRPosition::IRP_FLOAT:
564  break;
565  case IRPosition::IRP_FUNCTION:
566  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE:
567  return AttributeList::FunctionIndex;
568  case IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED:
569  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
570  return AttributeList::ReturnIndex;
571  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
572  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
573  return getCallSiteArgNo() + AttributeList::FirstArgIndex;
574  }
575  llvm_unreachable(
576  "There is no attribute index for a floating or invalid position!");
577  }
578 
579  /// Return the associated position kind.
580  Kind getPositionKind() const {
581  char EncodingBits = getEncodingBits();
582  if (EncodingBits == ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE)
583  return IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT;
584  if (EncodingBits == ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION)
585  return IRP_FLOAT;
586 
587  Value *V = getAsValuePtr();
588  if (!V)
589  return IRP_INVALID;
590  if (isa<Argument>(V))
591  return IRP_ARGUMENT;
592  if (isa<Function>(V))
593  return isReturnPosition(EncodingBits) ? IRP_RETURNED : IRP_FUNCTION;
594  if (isa<CallBase>(V))
595  return isReturnPosition(EncodingBits) ? IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED
596  : IRP_CALL_SITE;
597  return IRP_FLOAT;
598  }
599 
600  /// TODO: Figure out if the attribute related helper functions should live
601  /// here or somewhere else.
602 
603  /// Return true if any kind in \p AKs existing in the IR at a position that
604  /// will affect this one. See also getAttrs(...).
605  /// \param IgnoreSubsumingPositions Flag to determine if subsuming positions,
606  /// e.g., the function position if this is an
607  /// argument position, should be ignored.
608  bool hasAttr(ArrayRef<Attribute::AttrKind> AKs,
609  bool IgnoreSubsumingPositions = false,
610  Attributor *A = nullptr) const;
611 
612  /// Return the attributes of any kind in \p AKs existing in the IR at a
613  /// position that will affect this one. While each position can only have a
614  /// single attribute of any kind in \p AKs, there are "subsuming" positions
615  /// that could have an attribute as well. This method returns all attributes
616  /// found in \p Attrs.
617  /// \param IgnoreSubsumingPositions Flag to determine if subsuming positions,
618  /// e.g., the function position if this is an
619  /// argument position, should be ignored.
620  void getAttrs(ArrayRef<Attribute::AttrKind> AKs,
621  SmallVectorImpl<Attribute> &Attrs,
622  bool IgnoreSubsumingPositions = false,
623  Attributor *A = nullptr) const;
624 
625  /// Remove the attribute of kind \p AKs existing in the IR at this position.
626  void removeAttrs(ArrayRef<Attribute::AttrKind> AKs) const {
627  if (getPositionKind() == IRP_INVALID || getPositionKind() == IRP_FLOAT)
628  return;
629 
630  AttributeList AttrList;
631  auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&getAnchorValue());
632  if (CB)
633  AttrList = CB->getAttributes();
634  else
635  AttrList = getAssociatedFunction()->getAttributes();
636 
637  LLVMContext &Ctx = getAnchorValue().getContext();
638  for (Attribute::AttrKind AK : AKs)
639  AttrList = AttrList.removeAttributeAtIndex(Ctx, getAttrIdx(), AK);
640 
641  if (CB)
642  CB->setAttributes(AttrList);
643  else
644  getAssociatedFunction()->setAttributes(AttrList);
645  }
646 
647  bool isAnyCallSitePosition() const {
648  switch (getPositionKind()) {
649  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE:
650  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
651  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
652  return true;
653  default:
654  return false;
655  }
656  }
657 
658  /// Return true if the position is an argument or call site argument.
659  bool isArgumentPosition() const {
660  switch (getPositionKind()) {
661  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
662  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
663  return true;
664  default:
665  return false;
666  }
667  }
668 
669  /// Return the same position without the call base context.
670  IRPosition stripCallBaseContext() const {
671  IRPosition Result = *this;
672  Result.CBContext = nullptr;
673  return Result;
674  }
675 
676  /// Get the call base context from the position.
677  const CallBaseContext *getCallBaseContext() const { return CBContext; }
678 
679  /// Check if the position has any call base context.
680  bool hasCallBaseContext() const { return CBContext != nullptr; }
681 
682  /// Special DenseMap key values.
683  ///
684  ///{
685  static const IRPosition EmptyKey;
686  static const IRPosition TombstoneKey;
687  ///}
688 
689  /// Conversion into a void * to allow reuse of pointer hashing.
690  operator void *() const { return Enc.getOpaqueValue(); }
691 
692 private:
693  /// Private constructor for special values only!
694  explicit IRPosition(void *Ptr, const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr)
695  : CBContext(CBContext) {
696  Enc.setFromOpaqueValue(Ptr);
697  }
698 
699  /// IRPosition anchored at \p AnchorVal with kind/argument numbet \p PK.
700  explicit IRPosition(Value &AnchorVal, Kind PK,
701  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr)
702  : CBContext(CBContext) {
703  switch (PK) {
704  case IRPosition::IRP_INVALID:
705  llvm_unreachable("Cannot create invalid IRP with an anchor value!");
706  break;
707  case IRPosition::IRP_FLOAT:
708  // Special case for floating functions.
709  if (isa<Function>(AnchorVal) || isa<CallBase>(AnchorVal))
710  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION};
711  else
712  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_VALUE};
713  break;
714  case IRPosition::IRP_FUNCTION:
715  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE:
716  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_VALUE};
717  break;
718  case IRPosition::IRP_RETURNED:
719  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
720  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_RETURNED_VALUE};
721  break;
722  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
723  Enc = {&AnchorVal, ENC_VALUE};
724  break;
725  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
726  llvm_unreachable(
727  "Cannot create call site argument IRP with an anchor value!");
728  break;
729  }
730  verify();
731  }
732 
733  /// Return the callee argument number of the associated value if it is an
734  /// argument or call site argument. See also `getCalleeArgNo` and
735  /// `getCallSiteArgNo`.
736  int getArgNo(bool CallbackCalleeArgIfApplicable) const {
737  if (CallbackCalleeArgIfApplicable)
738  if (Argument *Arg = getAssociatedArgument())
739  return Arg->getArgNo();
740  switch (getPositionKind()) {
741  case IRPosition::IRP_ARGUMENT:
742  return cast<Argument>(getAsValuePtr())->getArgNo();
743  case IRPosition::IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT: {
744  Use &U = *getAsUsePtr();
745  return cast<CallBase>(U.getUser())->getArgOperandNo(&U);
746  }
747  default:
748  return -1;
749  }
750  }
751 
752  /// IRPosition for the use \p U. The position kind \p PK needs to be
753  /// IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT, the anchor value is the user, the associated value
754  /// the used value.
755  explicit IRPosition(Use &U, Kind PK) {
756  assert(PK == IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT &&
757  "Use constructor is for call site arguments only!");
758  Enc = {&U, ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE};
759  verify();
760  }
761 
762  /// Verify internal invariants.
763  void verify();
764 
765  /// Return the attributes of kind \p AK existing in the IR as attribute.
766  bool getAttrsFromIRAttr(Attribute::AttrKind AK,
767  SmallVectorImpl<Attribute> &Attrs) const;
768 
769  /// Return the attributes of kind \p AK existing in the IR as operand bundles
770  /// of an llvm.assume.
771  bool getAttrsFromAssumes(Attribute::AttrKind AK,
772  SmallVectorImpl<Attribute> &Attrs,
773  Attributor &A) const;
774 
775  /// Return the underlying pointer as Value *, valid for all positions but
776  /// IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT.
777  Value *getAsValuePtr() const {
778  assert(getEncodingBits() != ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE &&
779  "Not a value pointer!");
780  return reinterpret_cast<Value *>(Enc.getPointer());
781  }
782 
783  /// Return the underlying pointer as Use *, valid only for
784  /// IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT positions.
785  Use *getAsUsePtr() const {
786  assert(getEncodingBits() == ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE &&
787  "Not a value pointer!");
788  return reinterpret_cast<Use *>(Enc.getPointer());
789  }
790 
791  /// Return true if \p EncodingBits describe a returned or call site returned
792  /// position.
793  static bool isReturnPosition(char EncodingBits) {
794  return EncodingBits == ENC_RETURNED_VALUE;
795  }
796 
797  /// Return true if the encoding bits describe a returned or call site returned
798  /// position.
799  bool isReturnPosition() const { return isReturnPosition(getEncodingBits()); }
800 
801  /// The encoding of the IRPosition is a combination of a pointer and two
802  /// encoding bits. The values of the encoding bits are defined in the enum
803  /// below. The pointer is either a Value* (for the first three encoding bit
804  /// combinations) or Use* (for ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE).
805  ///
806  ///{
807  enum {
808  ENC_VALUE = 0b00,
809  ENC_RETURNED_VALUE = 0b01,
810  ENC_FLOATING_FUNCTION = 0b10,
811  ENC_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT_USE = 0b11,
812  };
813 
814  // Reserve the maximal amount of bits so there is no need to mask out the
815  // remaining ones. We will not encode anything else in the pointer anyway.
816  static constexpr int NumEncodingBits =
817  PointerLikeTypeTraits<void *>::NumLowBitsAvailable;
818  static_assert(NumEncodingBits >= 2, "At least two bits are required!");
819 
820  /// The pointer with the encoding bits.
821  PointerIntPair<void *, NumEncodingBits, char> Enc;
822  ///}
823 
824  /// Call base context. Used for callsite specific analysis.
825  const CallBaseContext *CBContext = nullptr;
826 
827  /// Return the encoding bits.
828  char getEncodingBits() const { return Enc.getInt(); }
829 };
830 
831 /// Helper that allows IRPosition as a key in a DenseMap.
832 template <> struct DenseMapInfo<IRPosition> {
833  static inline IRPosition getEmptyKey() { return IRPosition::EmptyKey; }
834  static inline IRPosition getTombstoneKey() {
835  return IRPosition::TombstoneKey;
836  }
837  static unsigned getHashValue(const IRPosition &IRP) {
838  return (DenseMapInfo<void *>::getHashValue(IRP) << 4) ^
839  (DenseMapInfo<Value *>::getHashValue(IRP.getCallBaseContext()));
840  }
841 
842  static bool isEqual(const IRPosition &a, const IRPosition &b) {
843  return a == b;
844  }
845 };
846 
847 /// A visitor class for IR positions.
848 ///
849 /// Given a position P, the SubsumingPositionIterator allows to visit "subsuming
850 /// positions" wrt. attributes/information. Thus, if a piece of information
851 /// holds for a subsuming position, it also holds for the position P.
852 ///
853 /// The subsuming positions always include the initial position and then,
854 /// depending on the position kind, additionally the following ones:
855 /// - for IRP_RETURNED:
856 /// - the function (IRP_FUNCTION)
857 /// - for IRP_ARGUMENT:
858 /// - the function (IRP_FUNCTION)
859 /// - for IRP_CALL_SITE:
860 /// - the callee (IRP_FUNCTION), if known
861 /// - for IRP_CALL_SITE_RETURNED:
862 /// - the callee (IRP_RETURNED), if known
863 /// - the call site (IRP_FUNCTION)
864 /// - the callee (IRP_FUNCTION), if known
865 /// - for IRP_CALL_SITE_ARGUMENT:
866 /// - the argument of the callee (IRP_ARGUMENT), if known
867 /// - the callee (IRP_FUNCTION), if known
868 /// - the position the call site argument is associated with if it is not
869 /// anchored to the call site, e.g., if it is an argument then the argument
870 /// (IRP_ARGUMENT)
871 class SubsumingPositionIterator {
872  SmallVector<IRPosition, 4> IRPositions;
873  using iterator = decltype(IRPositions)::iterator;
874 
875 public:
876  SubsumingPositionIterator(const IRPosition &IRP);
877  iterator begin() { return IRPositions.begin(); }
878  iterator end() { return IRPositions.end(); }
879 };
880 
881 /// Wrapper for FunctoinAnalysisManager.
882 struct AnalysisGetter {
883  template <typename Analysis>
884  typename Analysis::Result *getAnalysis(const Function &F) {
885  if (!FAM || !F.getParent())
886  return nullptr;
887  return &FAM->getResult<Analysis>(const_cast<Function &>(F));
888  }
889 
890  AnalysisGetter(FunctionAnalysisManager &FAM) : FAM(&FAM) {}
891  AnalysisGetter() = default;
892 
893 private:
894  FunctionAnalysisManager *FAM = nullptr;
895 };
896 
897 /// Data structure to hold cached (LLVM-IR) information.
898 ///
899 /// All attributes are given an InformationCache object at creation time to
900 /// avoid inspection of the IR by all of them individually. This default
901 /// InformationCache will hold information required by 'default' attributes,
902 /// thus the ones deduced when Attributor::identifyDefaultAbstractAttributes(..)
903 /// is called.
904 ///
905 /// If custom abstract attributes, registered manually through
906 /// Attributor::registerAA(...), need more information, especially if it is not
907 /// reusable, it is advised to inherit from the InformationCache and cast the
908 /// instance down in the abstract attributes.
909 struct InformationCache {
910  InformationCache(const Module &M, AnalysisGetter &AG,
911  BumpPtrAllocator &Allocator, SetVector<Function *> *CGSCC)
912  : DL(M.getDataLayout()), Allocator(Allocator),
913  Explorer(
914  /* ExploreInterBlock */ true, /* ExploreCFGForward */ true,
915  /* ExploreCFGBackward */ true,
916  /* LIGetter */
917  [&](const Function &F) { return AG.getAnalysis<LoopAnalysis>(F); },
918  /* DTGetter */
919  [&](const Function &F) {
920  return AG.getAnalysis<DominatorTreeAnalysis>(F);
921  },
922  /* PDTGetter */
923  [&](const Function &F) {
924  return AG.getAnalysis<PostDominatorTreeAnalysis>(F);
925  }),
926  AG(AG), TargetTriple(M.getTargetTriple()) {
927  if (CGSCC)
928  initializeModuleSlice(*CGSCC);
929  }
930 
931  ~InformationCache() {
932  // The FunctionInfo objects are allocated via a BumpPtrAllocator, we call
933  // the destructor manually.
934  for (auto &It : FuncInfoMap)
935  It.getSecond()->~FunctionInfo();
936  }
937 
938  /// Apply \p CB to all uses of \p F. If \p LookThroughConstantExprUses is
939  /// true, constant expression users are not given to \p CB but their uses are
940  /// traversed transitively.
941  template <typename CBTy>
942  static void foreachUse(Function &F, CBTy CB,
943  bool LookThroughConstantExprUses = true) {
944  SmallVector<Use *, 8> Worklist(make_pointer_range(F.uses()));
945 
946  for (unsigned Idx = 0; Idx < Worklist.size(); ++Idx) {
947  Use &U = *Worklist[Idx];
948 
949  // Allow use in constant bitcasts and simply look through them.
950  if (LookThroughConstantExprUses && isa<ConstantExpr>(U.getUser())) {
951  for (Use &CEU : cast<ConstantExpr>(U.getUser())->uses())
952  Worklist.push_back(&CEU);
953  continue;
954  }
955 
956  CB(U);
957  }
958  }
959 
960  /// Initialize the ModuleSlice member based on \p SCC. ModuleSlices contains
961  /// (a subset of) all functions that we can look at during this SCC traversal.
962  /// This includes functions (transitively) called from the SCC and the
963  /// (transitive) callers of SCC functions. We also can look at a function if
964  /// there is a "reference edge", i.a., if the function somehow uses (!=calls)
965  /// a function in the SCC or a caller of a function in the SCC.
966  void initializeModuleSlice(SetVector<Function *> &SCC) {
967  ModuleSlice.insert(SCC.begin(), SCC.end());
968 
969  SmallPtrSet<Function *, 16> Seen;
970  SmallVector<Function *, 16> Worklist(SCC.begin(), SCC.end());
971  while (!Worklist.empty()) {
972  Function *F = Worklist.pop_back_val();
973  ModuleSlice.insert(F);
974 
975  for (Instruction &I : instructions(*F))
976  if (auto *CB = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&I))
977  if (Function *Callee = CB->getCalledFunction())
978  if (Seen.insert(Callee).second)
979  Worklist.push_back(Callee);
980  }
981 
982  Seen.clear();
983  Worklist.append(SCC.begin(), SCC.end());
984  while (!Worklist.empty()) {
985  Function *F = Worklist.pop_back_val();
986  ModuleSlice.insert(F);
987 
988  // Traverse all transitive uses.
989  foreachUse(*F, [&](Use &U) {
990  if (auto *UsrI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()))
991  if (Seen.insert(UsrI->getFunction()).second)
992  Worklist.push_back(UsrI->getFunction());
993  });
994  }
995  }
996 
997  /// The slice of the module we are allowed to look at.
998  SmallPtrSet<Function *, 8> ModuleSlice;
999 
1000  /// A vector type to hold instructions.
1001  using InstructionVectorTy = SmallVector<Instruction *, 8>;
1002 
1003  /// A map type from opcodes to instructions with this opcode.
1004  using OpcodeInstMapTy = DenseMap<unsigned, InstructionVectorTy *>;
1005 
1006  /// Return the map that relates "interesting" opcodes with all instructions
1007  /// with that opcode in \p F.
1008  OpcodeInstMapTy &getOpcodeInstMapForFunction(const Function &F) {
1009  return getFunctionInfo(F).OpcodeInstMap;
1010  }
1011 
1012  /// Return the instructions in \p F that may read or write memory.
1013  InstructionVectorTy &getReadOrWriteInstsForFunction(const Function &F) {
1014  return getFunctionInfo(F).RWInsts;
1015  }
1016 
1017  /// Return MustBeExecutedContextExplorer
1018  MustBeExecutedContextExplorer &getMustBeExecutedContextExplorer() {
1019  return Explorer;
1020  }
1021 
1022  /// Return TargetLibraryInfo for function \p F.
1023  TargetLibraryInfo *getTargetLibraryInfoForFunction(const Function &F) {
1024  return AG.getAnalysis<TargetLibraryAnalysis>(F);
1025  }
1026 
1027  /// Return AliasAnalysis Result for function \p F.
1028  AAResults *getAAResultsForFunction(const Function &F);
1029 
1030  /// Return true if \p Arg is involved in a must-tail call, thus the argument
1031  /// of the caller or callee.
1032  bool isInvolvedInMustTailCall(const Argument &Arg) {
1033  FunctionInfo &FI = getFunctionInfo(*Arg.getParent());
1034  return FI.CalledViaMustTail || FI.ContainsMustTailCall;
1035  }
1036 
1037  /// Return the analysis result from a pass \p AP for function \p F.
1038  template <typename AP>
1039  typename AP::Result *getAnalysisResultForFunction(const Function &F) {
1040  return AG.getAnalysis<AP>(F);
1041  }
1042 
1043  /// Return datalayout used in the module.
1044  const DataLayout &getDL() { return DL; }
1045 
1046  /// Return the map conaining all the knowledge we have from `llvm.assume`s.
1047  const RetainedKnowledgeMap &getKnowledgeMap() const { return KnowledgeMap; }
1048 
1049  /// Return if \p To is potentially reachable form \p From or not
1050  /// If the same query was answered, return cached result
1051  bool getPotentiallyReachable(const Instruction &From, const Instruction &To) {
1052  auto KeyPair = std::make_pair(&From, &To);
1053  auto Iter = PotentiallyReachableMap.find(KeyPair);
1054  if (Iter != PotentiallyReachableMap.end())
1055  return Iter->second;
1056  const Function &F = *From.getFunction();
1057  bool Result = true;
1058  if (From.getFunction() == To.getFunction())
1059  Result = isPotentiallyReachable(&From, &To, nullptr,
1060  AG.getAnalysis<DominatorTreeAnalysis>(F),
1061  AG.getAnalysis<LoopAnalysis>(F));
1062  PotentiallyReachableMap.insert(std::make_pair(KeyPair, Result));
1063  return Result;
1064  }
1065 
1066  /// Check whether \p F is part of module slice.
1067  bool isInModuleSlice(const Function &F) {
1068  return ModuleSlice.count(const_cast<Function *>(&F));
1069  }
1070 
1071  /// Return true if the stack (llvm::Alloca) can be accessed by other threads.
1072  bool stackIsAccessibleByOtherThreads() { return !targetIsGPU(); }
1073 
1074  /// Return true if the target is a GPU.
1075  bool targetIsGPU() {
1076  return TargetTriple.isAMDGPU() || TargetTriple.isNVPTX();
1077  }
1078 
1079 private:
1080  struct FunctionInfo {
1081  ~FunctionInfo();
1082 
1083  /// A nested map that remembers all instructions in a function with a
1084  /// certain instruction opcode (Instruction::getOpcode()).
1085  OpcodeInstMapTy OpcodeInstMap;
1086 
1087  /// A map from functions to their instructions that may read or write
1088  /// memory.
1089  InstructionVectorTy RWInsts;
1090 
1091  /// Function is called by a `musttail` call.
1092  bool CalledViaMustTail;
1093 
1094  /// Function contains a `musttail` call.
1095  bool ContainsMustTailCall;
1096  };
1097 
1098  /// A map type from functions to informatio about it.
1099  DenseMap<const Function *, FunctionInfo *> FuncInfoMap;
1100 
1101  /// Return information about the function \p F, potentially by creating it.
1102  FunctionInfo &getFunctionInfo(const Function &F) {
1103  FunctionInfo *&FI = FuncInfoMap[&F];
1104  if (!FI) {
1105  FI = new (Allocator) FunctionInfo();
1106  initializeInformationCache(F, *FI);
1107  }
1108  return *FI;
1109  }
1110 
1111  /// Initialize the function information cache \p FI for the function \p F.
1112  ///
1113  /// This method needs to be called for all function that might be looked at
1114  /// through the information cache interface *prior* to looking at them.
1115  void initializeInformationCache(const Function &F, FunctionInfo &FI);
1116 
1117  /// The datalayout used in the module.
1118  const DataLayout &DL;
1119 
1120  /// The allocator used to allocate memory, e.g. for `FunctionInfo`s.
1121  BumpPtrAllocator &Allocator;
1122 
1123  /// MustBeExecutedContextExplorer
1124  MustBeExecutedContextExplorer Explorer;
1125 
1126  /// A map with knowledge retained in `llvm.assume` instructions.
1127  RetainedKnowledgeMap KnowledgeMap;
1128 
1129  /// Getters for analysis.
1130  AnalysisGetter &AG;
1131 
1132  /// Set of inlineable functions
1133  SmallPtrSet<const Function *, 8> InlineableFunctions;
1134 
1135  /// A map for caching results of queries for isPotentiallyReachable
1136  DenseMap<std::pair<const Instruction *, const Instruction *>, bool>
1137  PotentiallyReachableMap;
1138 
1139  /// The triple describing the target machine.
1140  Triple TargetTriple;
1141 
1142  /// Give the Attributor access to the members so
1143  /// Attributor::identifyDefaultAbstractAttributes(...) can initialize them.
1144  friend struct Attributor;
1145 };
1146 
1147 /// The fixpoint analysis framework that orchestrates the attribute deduction.
1148 ///
1149 /// The Attributor provides a general abstract analysis framework (guided
1150 /// fixpoint iteration) as well as helper functions for the deduction of
1151 /// (LLVM-IR) attributes. However, also other code properties can be deduced,
1152 /// propagated, and ultimately manifested through the Attributor framework. This
1153 /// is particularly useful if these properties interact with attributes and a
1154 /// co-scheduled deduction allows to improve the solution. Even if not, thus if
1155 /// attributes/properties are completely isolated, they should use the
1156 /// Attributor framework to reduce the number of fixpoint iteration frameworks
1157 /// in the code base. Note that the Attributor design makes sure that isolated
1158 /// attributes are not impacted, in any way, by others derived at the same time
1159 /// if there is no cross-reasoning performed.
1160 ///
1161 /// The public facing interface of the Attributor is kept simple and basically
1162 /// allows abstract attributes to one thing, query abstract attributes
1163 /// in-flight. There are two reasons to do this:
1164 /// a) The optimistic state of one abstract attribute can justify an
1165 /// optimistic state of another, allowing to framework to end up with an
1166 /// optimistic (=best possible) fixpoint instead of one based solely on
1167 /// information in the IR.
1168 /// b) This avoids reimplementing various kinds of lookups, e.g., to check
1169 /// for existing IR attributes, in favor of a single lookups interface
1170 /// provided by an abstract attribute subclass.
1171 ///
1172 /// NOTE: The mechanics of adding a new "concrete" abstract attribute are
1173 /// described in the file comment.
1174 struct Attributor {
1175 
1176  using OptimizationRemarkGetter =
1177  function_ref<OptimizationRemarkEmitter &(Function *)>;
1178 
1179  /// Constructor
1180  ///
1181  /// \param Functions The set of functions we are deriving attributes for.
1182  /// \param InfoCache Cache to hold various information accessible for
1183  /// the abstract attributes.
1184  /// \param CGUpdater Helper to update an underlying call graph.
1185  /// \param Allowed If not null, a set limiting the attribute opportunities.
1186  /// \param DeleteFns Whether to delete functions.
1187  /// \param RewriteSignatures Whether to rewrite function signatures.
1188  Attributor(SetVector<Function *> &Functions, InformationCache &InfoCache,
1189  CallGraphUpdater &CGUpdater,
1190  DenseSet<const char *> *Allowed = nullptr, bool DeleteFns = true,
1191  bool RewriteSignatures = true)
1192  : Allocator(InfoCache.Allocator), Functions(Functions),
1193  InfoCache(InfoCache), CGUpdater(CGUpdater), Allowed(Allowed),
1194  DeleteFns(DeleteFns), RewriteSignatures(RewriteSignatures),
1195  MaxFixpointIterations(None), OREGetter(None), PassName("") {}
1196 
1197  /// Constructor
1198  ///
1199  /// \param Functions The set of functions we are deriving attributes for.
1200  /// \param InfoCache Cache to hold various information accessible for
1201  /// the abstract attributes.
1202  /// \param CGUpdater Helper to update an underlying call graph.
1203  /// \param Allowed If not null, a set limiting the attribute opportunities.
1204  /// \param DeleteFns Whether to delete functions
1205  /// \param RewriteSignatures Whether to rewrite function signatures.
1206  /// \param MaxFixpointIterations Maximum number of iterations to run until
1207  /// fixpoint.
1208  /// \param OREGetter A callback function that returns an ORE object from a
1209  /// Function pointer.
1210  /// \param PassName The name of the pass emitting remarks.
1211  Attributor(SetVector<Function *> &Functions, InformationCache &InfoCache,
1212  CallGraphUpdater &CGUpdater, DenseSet<const char *> *Allowed,
1213  bool DeleteFns, bool RewriteSignatures,
1214  Optional<unsigned> MaxFixpointIterations,
1215  OptimizationRemarkGetter OREGetter, const char *PassName)
1216  : Allocator(InfoCache.Allocator), Functions(Functions),
1217  InfoCache(InfoCache), CGUpdater(CGUpdater), Allowed(Allowed),
1218  DeleteFns(DeleteFns), RewriteSignatures(RewriteSignatures),
1219  MaxFixpointIterations(MaxFixpointIterations),
1220  OREGetter(Optional<OptimizationRemarkGetter>(OREGetter)),
1221  PassName(PassName) {}

1225  /// Run the analyses until a fixpoint is reached or enforced (timeout).
1226  ///
1227  /// The attributes registered with this Attributor can be used after as long
1228  /// as the Attributor is not destroyed (it owns the attributes now).
1229  ///
1230  /// \Returns CHANGED if the IR was changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
1231  ChangeStatus run();
1232 
1233  /// Lookup an abstract attribute of type \p AAType at position \p IRP. While
1234  /// no abstract attribute is found equivalent positions are checked, see
1235  /// SubsumingPositionIterator. Thus, the returned abstract attribute
1236  /// might be anchored at a different position, e.g., the callee if \p IRP is a
1237  /// call base.
1238  ///
1239  /// This method is the only (supported) way an abstract attribute can retrieve
1240  /// information from another abstract attribute. As an example, take an
1241  /// abstract attribute that determines the memory access behavior for a
1242  /// argument (readnone, readonly, ...). It should use `getAAFor` to get the
1243  /// most optimistic information for other abstract attributes in-flight, e.g.
1244  /// the one reasoning about the "captured" state for the argument or the one
1245  /// reasoning on the memory access behavior of the function as a whole.
1246  ///
1247  /// If the DepClass enum is set to `DepClassTy::None` the dependence from
1248  /// \p QueryingAA to the return abstract attribute is not automatically
1249  /// recorded. This should only be used if the caller will record the
1250  /// dependence explicitly if necessary, thus if it the returned abstract
1251  /// attribute is used for reasoning. To record the dependences explicitly use
1252  /// the `Attributor::recordDependence` method.
1253  template <typename AAType>
1254  const AAType &getAAFor(const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA,
1255  const IRPosition &IRP, DepClassTy DepClass) {
1256  return getOrCreateAAFor<AAType>(IRP, &QueryingAA, DepClass,
1257  /* ForceUpdate */ false);
1258  }
1259 
1260  /// Similar to getAAFor but the return abstract attribute will be updated (via
1261  /// `AbstractAttribute::update`) even if it is found in the cache. This is
1262  /// especially useful for AAIsDead as changes in liveness can make updates
1263  /// possible/useful that were not happening before as the abstract attribute
1264  /// was assumed dead.
1265  template <typename AAType>
1266  const AAType &getAndUpdateAAFor(const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA,
1267  const IRPosition &IRP, DepClassTy DepClass) {
1268  return getOrCreateAAFor<AAType>(IRP, &QueryingAA, DepClass,
1269  /* ForceUpdate */ true);
1270  }
1271 
1272  /// The version of getAAFor that allows to omit a querying abstract
1273  /// attribute. Using this after Attributor started running is restricted to
1274  /// only the Attributor itself. Initial seeding of AAs can be done via this
1275  /// function.
1276  /// NOTE: ForceUpdate is ignored in any stage other than the update stage.
1277  template <typename AAType>
1278  const AAType &getOrCreateAAFor(IRPosition IRP,
1279  const AbstractAttribute *QueryingAA,
1280  DepClassTy DepClass, bool ForceUpdate = false,
1281  bool UpdateAfterInit = true) {
1282  if (!shouldPropagateCallBaseContext(IRP))
1283  IRP = IRP.stripCallBaseContext();
1284 
1285  if (AAType *AAPtr = lookupAAFor<AAType>(IRP, QueryingAA, DepClass,
1286  /* AllowInvalidState */ true)) {
1287  if (ForceUpdate && Phase == AttributorPhase::UPDATE)
1288  updateAA(*AAPtr);
1289  return *AAPtr;
1290  }
1291 
1292  // No matching attribute found, create one.
1293  // Use the static create method.
1294  auto &AA = AAType::createForPosition(IRP, *this);
1295 
1296  // If we are currenty seeding attributes, enforce seeding rules.
1297  if (Phase == AttributorPhase::SEEDING && !shouldSeedAttribute(AA)) {
1298  AA.getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
1299  return AA;
1300  }
1301 
1302  registerAA(AA);
1303 
1304  // For now we ignore naked and optnone functions.
1305  bool Invalidate = Allowed && !Allowed->count(&AAType::ID);
1306  const Function *FnScope = IRP.getAnchorScope();
1307  if (FnScope)
1308  Invalidate |= FnScope->hasFnAttribute(Attribute::Naked) ||
1309  FnScope->hasFnAttribute(Attribute::OptimizeNone);
1310 
1311  // Avoid too many nested initializations to prevent a stack overflow.
1312  Invalidate |= InitializationChainLength > MaxInitializationChainLength;
1313 
1314  // Bootstrap the new attribute with an initial update to propagate
1315  // information, e.g., function -> call site. If it is not on a given
1316  // Allowed we will not perform updates at all.
1317  if (Invalidate) {
1318  AA.getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
1319  return AA;
1320  }
1321 
1322  {
1323  TimeTraceScope TimeScope(AA.getName() + "::initialize");
1324  ++InitializationChainLength;
1325  AA.initialize(*this);
1326  --InitializationChainLength;
1327  }
1328 
1329  // Initialize and update is allowed for code outside of the current function
1330  // set, but only if it is part of module slice we are allowed to look at.
1331  // Only exception is AAIsDeadFunction whose initialization is prevented
1332  // directly, since we don't to compute it twice.
1333  if (FnScope && !Functions.count(const_cast<Function *>(FnScope))) {
1334  if (!getInfoCache().isInModuleSlice(*FnScope)) {
1335  AA.getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
1336  return AA;
1337  }
1338  }
1339 
1340  // If this is queried in the manifest stage, we force the AA to indicate
1341  // pessimistic fixpoint immediately.
1342  if (Phase == AttributorPhase::MANIFEST) {
1343  AA.getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
1344  return AA;
1345  }
1346 
1347  // Allow seeded attributes to declare dependencies.
1348  // Remember the seeding state.
1349  if (UpdateAfterInit) {
1350  AttributorPhase OldPhase = Phase;
1351  Phase = AttributorPhase::UPDATE;
1352 
1353  updateAA(AA);
1354 
1355  Phase = OldPhase;
1356  }
1357 
1358  if (QueryingAA && AA.getState().isValidState())
1359  recordDependence(AA, const_cast<AbstractAttribute &>(*QueryingAA),
1360  DepClass);
1361  return AA;
1362  }
1363  template <typename AAType>
1364  const AAType &getOrCreateAAFor(const IRPosition &IRP) {
1365  return getOrCreateAAFor<AAType>(IRP, /* QueryingAA */ nullptr,
1366  DepClassTy::NONE);
1367  }
1368 
1369  /// Return the attribute of \p AAType for \p IRP if existing and valid. This
1370  /// also allows non-AA users lookup.
1371  template <typename AAType>
1372  AAType *lookupAAFor(const IRPosition &IRP,
1373  const AbstractAttribute *QueryingAA = nullptr,
1374  DepClassTy DepClass = DepClassTy::OPTIONAL,
1375  bool AllowInvalidState = false) {
1376  static_assert(std::is_base_of<AbstractAttribute, AAType>::value,
1377  "Cannot query an attribute with a type not derived from "
1378  "'AbstractAttribute'!");
1379  // Lookup the abstract attribute of type AAType. If found, return it after
1380  // registering a dependence of QueryingAA on the one returned attribute.
1381  AbstractAttribute *AAPtr = AAMap.lookup({&AAType::ID, IRP});
1382  if (!AAPtr)
1383  return nullptr;
1384 
1385  AAType *AA = static_cast<AAType *>(AAPtr);
1386 
1387  // Do not register a dependence on an attribute with an invalid state.
1388  if (DepClass != DepClassTy::NONE && QueryingAA &&
1389  AA->getState().isValidState())
1390  recordDependence(*AA, const_cast<AbstractAttribute &>(*QueryingAA),
1391  DepClass);
1392 
1393  // Return nullptr if this attribute has an invalid state.
1394  if (!AllowInvalidState && !AA->getState().isValidState())
1395  return nullptr;
1396  return AA;
1397  }
1398 
1399  /// Allows a query AA to request an update if a new query was received.
1400  void registerForUpdate(AbstractAttribute &AA);
1401 
1402  /// Explicitly record a dependence from \p FromAA to \p ToAA, that is if
1403  /// \p FromAA changes \p ToAA should be updated as well.
1404  ///
1405  /// This method should be used in conjunction with the `getAAFor` method and
1406  /// with the DepClass enum passed to the method set to None. This can
1407  /// be beneficial to avoid false dependences but it requires the users of
1408  /// `getAAFor` to explicitly record true dependences through this method.
1409  /// The \p DepClass flag indicates if the dependence is striclty necessary.
1410  /// That means for required dependences, if \p FromAA changes to an invalid
1411  /// state, \p ToAA can be moved to a pessimistic fixpoint because it required
1412  /// information from \p FromAA but none are available anymore.
1413  void recordDependence(const AbstractAttribute &FromAA,
1414  const AbstractAttribute &ToAA, DepClassTy DepClass);
1415 
1416  /// Introduce a new abstract attribute into the fixpoint analysis.
1417  ///
1418  /// Note that ownership of the attribute is given to the Attributor. It will
1419  /// invoke delete for the Attributor on destruction of the Attributor.
1420  ///
1421  /// Attributes are identified by their IR position (AAType::getIRPosition())
1422  /// and the address of their static member (see AAType::ID).
1423  template <typename AAType> AAType &registerAA(AAType &AA) {
1424  static_assert(std::is_base_of<AbstractAttribute, AAType>::value,
1425  "Cannot register an attribute with a type not derived from "
1426  "'AbstractAttribute'!");
1427  // Put the attribute in the lookup map structure and the container we use to
1428  // keep track of all attributes.
1429  const IRPosition &IRP = AA.getIRPosition();
1430  AbstractAttribute *&AAPtr = AAMap[{&AAType::ID, IRP}];
1431 
1432  assert(!AAPtr && "Attribute already in map!");
1433  AAPtr = &AA;
1434 
1435  // Register AA with the synthetic root only before the manifest stage.
1436  if (Phase == AttributorPhase::SEEDING || Phase == AttributorPhase::UPDATE)
1437  DG.SyntheticRoot.Deps.push_back(
1438  AADepGraphNode::DepTy(&AA, unsigned(DepClassTy::REQUIRED)));
1439 
1440  return AA;
1441  }

1444  InformationCache &getInfoCache() { return InfoCache; }

1446  /// Return true if this is a module pass, false otherwise.
1447  bool isModulePass() const {
1448  return !Functions.empty() &&
1449  Functions.size() == Functions.front()->getParent()->size();
1450  }

1453  bool isRunOn(Function &Fn) const {
1454  return Functions.empty() || Functions.count(&Fn);
1455  }

1457  /// Determine opportunities to derive 'default' attributes in \p F and create
1458  /// abstract attribute objects for them.
1459  ///
1460  /// \param F The function that is checked for attribute opportunities.
1461  ///
1462  /// Note that abstract attribute instances are generally created even if the
1463  /// IR already contains the information they would deduce. The most important
1464  /// reason for this is the single interface, the one of the abstract attribute
1465  /// instance, which can be queried without the need to look at the IR in
1466  /// various places.
1467  void identifyDefaultAbstractAttributes(Function &F);

1469  /// Determine whether the function \p F is IPO amendable
1470  ///
1471  /// If a function is exactly defined or it has alwaysinline attribute
1472  /// and is viable to be inlined, we say it is IPO amendable
1473  bool isFunctionIPOAmendable(const Function &F) {
1474  return F.hasExactDefinition() || InfoCache.InlineableFunctions.count(&F);
1475  }

1477  /// Mark the internal function \p F as live.
1478  ///
1479  /// This will trigger the identification and initialization of attributes for
1480  /// \p F.
1481  void markLiveInternalFunction(const Function &F) {
1482  assert(F.hasLocalLinkage() &&
1483  "Only local linkage is assumed dead initially.");
1484 
1485  identifyDefaultAbstractAttributes(const_cast<Function &>(F));
1486  }

1496  /// Record that \p U is to be replaces with \p NV after information was
1497  /// manifested. This also triggers deletion of trivially dead istructions.
1498  bool changeUseAfterManifest(Use &U, Value &NV) {
1499  Value *&V = ToBeChangedUses[&U];
1500  if (V && (V->stripPointerCasts() == NV.stripPointerCasts() ||
1501  isa_and_nonnull<UndefValue>(V)))
1502  return false;
1503  assert((!V || V == &NV || isa<UndefValue>(NV)) &&
1504  "Use was registered twice for replacement with different values!");
1505  V = &NV;
1506  return true;
1507  }
1508 
1509  /// Helper function to replace all uses of \p V with \p NV. Return true if
1510  /// there is any change. The flag \p ChangeDroppable indicates if dropppable
1511  /// uses should be changed too.
1512  bool changeValueAfterManifest(Value &V, Value &NV,
1513  bool ChangeDroppable = true) {
1514  auto &Entry = ToBeChangedValues[&V];
1515  Value *&CurNV = Entry.first;
1516  if (CurNV && (CurNV->stripPointerCasts() == NV.stripPointerCasts() ||
1517  isa<UndefValue>(CurNV)))
1518  return false;
1519  assert((!CurNV || CurNV == &NV || isa<UndefValue>(NV)) &&
1520  "Value replacement was registered twice with different values!");
1521  CurNV = &NV;
1522  Entry.second = ChangeDroppable;
1523  return true;
1524  }

1659  /// Check \p Pred on all (transitive) uses of \p V.
1660  ///
1661  /// This method will evaluate \p Pred on all (transitive) uses of the
1662  /// associated value and return true if \p Pred holds every time.
1663  /// If uses are skipped in favor of equivalent ones, e.g., if we look through
1664  /// memory, the \p EquivalentUseCB will be used to give the caller an idea
1665  /// what original used was replaced by a new one (or new ones). The visit is
1666  /// cut short if \p EquivalentUseCB returns false and the function will return
1667  /// false as well.
1668  bool checkForAllUses(function_ref<bool(const Use &, bool &)> Pred,
1669  const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA, const Value &V,
1670  bool CheckBBLivenessOnly = false,
1671  DepClassTy LivenessDepClass = DepClassTy::OPTIONAL,
1672  function_ref<bool(const Use &OldU, const Use &NewU)>
1673  EquivalentUseCB = nullptr);

1675  /// Emit a remark generically.
1676  ///
1677  /// This template function can be used to generically emit a remark. The
1678  /// RemarkKind should be one of the following:
1679  /// - OptimizationRemark to indicate a successful optimization attempt
1680  /// - OptimizationRemarkMissed to report a failed optimization attempt
1681  /// - OptimizationRemarkAnalysis to provide additional information about an
1682  /// optimization attempt
1683  ///
1684  /// The remark is built using a callback function \p RemarkCB that takes a
1685  /// RemarkKind as input and returns a RemarkKind.
1686  template <typename RemarkKind, typename RemarkCallBack>
1687  void emitRemark(Instruction *I, StringRef RemarkName,
1688  RemarkCallBack &&RemarkCB) const {
1689  if (!OREGetter)
1690  return;
1691 
1692  Function *F = I->getFunction();
1693  auto &ORE = OREGetter.getValue()(F);
1694 
1695  if (RemarkName.startswith("OMP"))
1696  ORE.emit([&]() {
1697  return RemarkCB(RemarkKind(PassName, RemarkName, I))
1698  << " [" << RemarkName << "]";
1699  });
1700  else
1701  ORE.emit([&]() { return RemarkCB(RemarkKind(PassName, RemarkName, I)); });
1702  }
1703 
1704  /// Emit a remark on a function.
1705  template <typename RemarkKind, typename RemarkCallBack>
1706  void emitRemark(Function *F, StringRef RemarkName,
1707  RemarkCallBack &&RemarkCB) const {
1708  if (!OREGetter)
1709  return;
1710 
1711  auto &ORE = OREGetter.getValue()(F);
1712 
1713  if (RemarkName.startswith("OMP"))
1714  ORE.emit([&]() {
1715  return RemarkCB(RemarkKind(PassName, RemarkName, F))
1716  << " [" << RemarkName << "]";
1717  });
1718  else
1719  ORE.emit([&]() { return RemarkCB(RemarkKind(PassName, RemarkName, F)); });
1720  }
1721 
1722  /// Helper struct used in the communication between an abstract attribute (AA)
1723  /// that wants to change the signature of a function and the Attributor which
1724  /// applies the changes. The struct is partially initialized with the
1725  /// information from the AA (see the constructor). All other members are
1726  /// provided by the Attributor prior to invoking any callbacks.
1727  struct ArgumentReplacementInfo {
1728  /// Callee repair callback type
1729  ///
1730  /// The function repair callback is invoked once to rewire the replacement
1731  /// arguments in the body of the new function. The argument replacement info
1732  /// is passed, as build from the registerFunctionSignatureRewrite call, as
1733  /// well as the replacement function and an iteratore to the first
1734  /// replacement argument.
1735  using CalleeRepairCBTy = std::function<void(
1736  const ArgumentReplacementInfo &, Function &, Function::arg_iterator)>;
1737 
1738  /// Abstract call site (ACS) repair callback type
1739  ///
1740  /// The abstract call site repair callback is invoked once on every abstract
1741  /// call site of the replaced function (\see ReplacedFn). The callback needs
1742  /// to provide the operands for the call to the new replacement function.
1743  /// The number and type of the operands appended to the provided vector
1744  /// (second argument) is defined by the number and types determined through
1745  /// the replacement type vector (\see ReplacementTypes). The first argument
1746  /// is the ArgumentReplacementInfo object registered with the Attributor
1747  /// through the registerFunctionSignatureRewrite call.
1748  using ACSRepairCBTy =
1749  std::function<void(const ArgumentReplacementInfo &, AbstractCallSite,
1750  SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &)>;
1751 
1752  /// Simple getters, see the corresponding members for details.
1753  ///{
1754 
1755  Attributor &getAttributor() const { return A; }
1756  const Function &getReplacedFn() const { return ReplacedFn; }
1757  const Argument &getReplacedArg() const { return ReplacedArg; }
1758  unsigned getNumReplacementArgs() const { return ReplacementTypes.size(); }
1759  const SmallVectorImpl<Type *> &getReplacementTypes() const {
1760  return ReplacementTypes;
1761  }
1762 
1763  ///}
1764 
1765  private:
1766  /// Constructor that takes the argument to be replaced, the types of
1767  /// the replacement arguments, as well as callbacks to repair the call sites
1768  /// and new function after the replacement happened.
1769  ArgumentReplacementInfo(Attributor &A, Argument &Arg,
1770  ArrayRef<Type *> ReplacementTypes,
1771  CalleeRepairCBTy &&CalleeRepairCB,
1772  ACSRepairCBTy &&ACSRepairCB)
1773  : A(A), ReplacedFn(*Arg.getParent()), ReplacedArg(Arg),
1774  ReplacementTypes(ReplacementTypes.begin(), ReplacementTypes.end()),
1775  CalleeRepairCB(std::move(CalleeRepairCB)),
1776  ACSRepairCB(std::move(ACSRepairCB)) {}
1777 
1778  /// Reference to the attributor to allow access from the callbacks.
1779  Attributor &A;
1780 
1781  /// The "old" function replaced by ReplacementFn.
1782  const Function &ReplacedFn;
1783 
1784  /// The "old" argument replaced by new ones defined via ReplacementTypes.
1785  const Argument &ReplacedArg;
1786 
1787  /// The types of the arguments replacing ReplacedArg.
1788  const SmallVector<Type *, 8> ReplacementTypes;
1789 
1790  /// Callee repair callback, see CalleeRepairCBTy.
1791  const CalleeRepairCBTy CalleeRepairCB;
1792 
1793  /// Abstract call site (ACS) repair callback, see ACSRepairCBTy.
1794  const ACSRepairCBTy ACSRepairCB;
1795 
1796  /// Allow access to the private members from the Attributor.
1797  friend struct Attributor;
1798  };

1839  /// all call sites are known, hence the function has internal linkage.

1841  /// information was used to skip or simplify potential call sites.

1899  /// Create a shallow wrapper for \p F such that \p F has internal linkage
1900  /// afterwards. It also sets the original \p F 's name to anonymous
1901  ///
1902  /// A wrapper is a function with the same type (and attributes) as \p F
1903  /// that will only call \p F and return the result, if any.
1904  ///
1905  /// Assuming the declaration of looks like:
1906  /// rty F(aty0 arg0, ..., atyN argN);
1907  ///
1908  /// The wrapper will then look as follows:
1909  /// rty wrapper(aty0 arg0, ..., atyN argN) {
1910  /// return F(arg0, ..., argN);
1911  /// }
1912  ///
1913  static void createShallowWrapper(Function &F);
1914 
1915  /// Returns true if the function \p F can be internalized. i.e. it has a
1916  /// compatible linkage.
1917  static bool isInternalizable(Function &F);
1918 
1919  /// Make another copy of the function \p F such that the copied version has
1920  /// internal linkage afterwards and can be analysed. Then we replace all uses
1921  /// of the original function to the copied one
1922  ///
1923  /// Only non-locally linked functions that have `linkonce_odr` or `weak_odr`
1924  /// linkage can be internalized because these linkages guarantee that other
1925  /// definitions with the same name have the same semantics as this one.
1926  ///
1927  /// This will only be run if the `attributor-allow-deep-wrappers` option is
1928  /// set, or if the function is called with \p Force set to true.
1929  ///
1930  /// If the function \p F failed to be internalized the return value will be a
1931  /// null pointer.
1932  static Function *internalizeFunction(Function &F, bool Force = false);
1933 
1934  /// Make copies of each function in the set \p FnSet such that the copied
1935  /// version has internal linkage afterwards and can be analysed. Then we
1936  /// replace all uses of the original function to the copied one. The map
1937  /// \p FnMap contains a mapping of functions to their internalized versions.
1938  ///
1939  /// Only non-locally linked functions that have `linkonce_odr` or `weak_odr`
1940  /// linkage can be internalized because these linkages guarantee that other
1941  /// definitions with the same name have the same semantics as this one.
1942  ///
1943  /// This version will internalize all the functions in the set \p FnSet at
1944  /// once and then replace the uses. This prevents internalized functions being
1945  /// called by external functions when there is an internalized version in the
1946  /// module.

1948  DenseMap<Function *, Function *> &FnMap);
