2107 
2108 /// An interface to query the internal state of an abstract attribute.
2109 ///
2110 /// The abstract state is a minimal interface that allows the Attributor to
2111 /// communicate with the abstract attributes about their internal state without
2112 /// enforcing or exposing implementation details, e.g., the (existence of an)
2113 /// underlying lattice.
2114 ///
2115 /// It is sufficient to be able to query if a state is (1) valid or invalid, (2)
2116 /// at a fixpoint, and to indicate to the state that (3) an optimistic fixpoint
2117 /// was reached or (4) a pessimistic fixpoint was enforced.
2118 ///
2119 /// All methods need to be implemented by the subclass. For the common use case,
2120 /// a single boolean state or a bit-encoded state, the BooleanState and
2121 /// {Inc,Dec,Bit}IntegerState classes are already provided. An abstract
2122 /// attribute can inherit from them to get the abstract state interface and
2123 /// additional methods to directly modify the state based if needed. See the
2124 /// class comments for help.
2125 struct AbstractState {
2126  virtual ~AbstractState() = default;
2127 
2128  /// Return if this abstract state is in a valid state. If false, no
2129  /// information provided should be used.
2130  virtual bool isValidState() const = 0;
2131 
2132  /// Return if this abstract state is fixed, thus does not need to be updated
2133  /// if information changes as it cannot change itself.
2134  virtual bool isAtFixpoint() const = 0;
2135 
2136  /// Indicate that the abstract state should converge to the optimistic state.
2137  ///
2138  /// This will usually make the optimistically assumed state the known to be
2139  /// true state.
2140  ///
2141  /// \returns ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED as the assumed value should not change.
2142  virtual ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() = 0;
2143 
2144  /// Indicate that the abstract state should converge to the pessimistic state.
2145  ///
2146  /// This will usually revert the optimistically assumed state to the known to
2147  /// be true state.
2148  ///
2149  /// \returns ChangeStatus::CHANGED as the assumed value may change.
2150  virtual ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() = 0;
2151 };
2152 
2153 /// Simple state with integers encoding.
2154 ///
2155 /// The interface ensures that the assumed bits are always a subset of the known
2156 /// bits. Users can only add known bits and, except through adding known bits,
2157 /// they can only remove assumed bits. This should guarantee monotoniticy and
2158 /// thereby the existence of a fixpoint (if used corretly). The fixpoint is
2159 /// reached when the assumed and known state/bits are equal. Users can
2160 /// force/inidicate a fixpoint. If an optimistic one is indicated, the known
2161 /// state will catch up with the assumed one, for a pessimistic fixpoint it is
2162 /// the other way around.
2163 template <typename base_ty, base_ty BestState, base_ty WorstState>
2164 struct IntegerStateBase : public AbstractState {
2165  using base_t = base_ty;
2166 
2167  IntegerStateBase() = default;
2168  IntegerStateBase(base_t Assumed) : Assumed(Assumed) {}
2169 
2170  /// Return the best possible representable state.
2171  static constexpr base_t getBestState() { return BestState; }
2172  static constexpr base_t getBestState(const IntegerStateBase &) {
2173  return getBestState();
2174  }
2175 
2176  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
2177  static constexpr base_t getWorstState() { return WorstState; }
2178  static constexpr base_t getWorstState(const IntegerStateBase &) {
2179  return getWorstState();
2180  }
2181 
2182  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
2183  /// NOTE: For now we simply pretend that the worst possible state is invalid.
2184  bool isValidState() const override { return Assumed != getWorstState(); }
2185 
2186  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
2187  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return Assumed == Known; }
2188 
2189  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
2190  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
2191  Known = Assumed;
2192  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2193  }
2194 
2195  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
2196  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
2197  Assumed = Known;
2198  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2199  }
2200 
2201  /// Return the known state encoding
2202  base_t getKnown() const { return Known; }
2203 
2204  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
2205  base_t getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
2206 
2207  /// Equality for IntegerStateBase.
2208  bool
2209  operator==(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) const {
2210  return this->getAssumed() == R.getAssumed() &&
2211  this->getKnown() == R.getKnown();
2212  }
2213 
2214  /// Inequality for IntegerStateBase.
2215  bool
2216  operator!=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) const {
2217  return !(*this == R);
2218  }
2219 
2220  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
2221  /// intended that only information assumed in both states will be assumed in
2222  /// this one afterwards.
2223  void operator^=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2224  handleNewAssumedValue(R.getAssumed());
2225  }
2226 
2227  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
2228  /// intended that information known in either state will be known in
2229  /// this one afterwards.
2230  void operator+=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2231  handleNewKnownValue(R.getKnown());
2232  }
2233 
2234  void operator|=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2235  joinOR(R.getAssumed(), R.getKnown());
2236  }
2237 
2238  void operator&=(const IntegerStateBase<base_t, BestState, WorstState> &R) {
2239  joinAND(R.getAssumed(), R.getKnown());
2240  }
2241 
2242 protected:
2243  /// Handle a new assumed value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2244  virtual void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) = 0;
2245 
2246  /// Handle a new known value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2247  virtual void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) = 0;
2248 
2249  /// Handle a value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2250  virtual void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) = 0;
2251 
2252  /// Handle a new assumed value \p Value. Subtype dependent.
2253  virtual void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) = 0;
2254 
2255  /// The known state encoding in an integer of type base_t.
2256  base_t Known = getWorstState();
2257 
2258  /// The assumed state encoding in an integer of type base_t.
2259  base_t Assumed = getBestState();
2260 };
2261 
2262 /// Specialization of the integer state for a bit-wise encoding.
2263 template <typename base_ty = uint32_t, base_ty BestState = ~base_ty(0),
2264  base_ty WorstState = 0>
2265 struct BitIntegerState
2266  : public IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> {
2267  using base_t = base_ty;
2268 
2269  /// Return true if the bits set in \p BitsEncoding are "known bits".
2270  bool isKnown(base_t BitsEncoding) const {
2271  return (this->Known & BitsEncoding) == BitsEncoding;
2272  }
2273 
2274  /// Return true if the bits set in \p BitsEncoding are "assumed bits".
2275  bool isAssumed(base_t BitsEncoding) const {
2276  return (this->Assumed & BitsEncoding) == BitsEncoding;
2277  }
2278 
2279  /// Add the bits in \p BitsEncoding to the "known bits".
2280  BitIntegerState &addKnownBits(base_t Bits) {
2281  // Make sure we never miss any "known bits".
2282  this->Assumed |= Bits;
2283  this->Known |= Bits;
2284  return *this;
2285  }
2286 
2287  /// Remove the bits in \p BitsEncoding from the "assumed bits" if not known.
2288  BitIntegerState &removeAssumedBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
2289  return intersectAssumedBits(~BitsEncoding);
2290  }
2291 
2292  /// Remove the bits in \p BitsEncoding from the "known bits".
2293  BitIntegerState &removeKnownBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
2294  this->Known = (this->Known & ~BitsEncoding);
2295  return *this;
2296  }
2297 
2298  /// Keep only "assumed bits" also set in \p BitsEncoding but all known ones.
2299  BitIntegerState &intersectAssumedBits(base_t BitsEncoding) {
2300  // Make sure we never loose any "known bits".
2301  this->Assumed = (this->Assumed & BitsEncoding) | this->Known;
2302  return *this;
2303  }
2304 
2305 private:
2306  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2307  intersectAssumedBits(Value);
2308  }
2309  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override { addKnownBits(Value); }
2310  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2311  this->Known |= KnownValue;
2312  this->Assumed |= AssumedValue;
2313  }
2314  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2315  this->Known &= KnownValue;
2316  this->Assumed &= AssumedValue;
2317  }
2318 };
2319 
2320 /// Specialization of the integer state for an increasing value, hence ~0u is
2321 /// the best state and 0 the worst.
2322 template <typename base_ty = uint32_t, base_ty BestState = ~base_ty(0),
2323  base_ty WorstState = 0>
2324 struct IncIntegerState
2325  : public IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> {
2326  using super = IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState>;
2327  using base_t = base_ty;
2328 
2329  IncIntegerState() : super() {}
2330  IncIntegerState(base_t Assumed) : super(Assumed) {}
2331 
2332  /// Return the best possible representable state.
2333  static constexpr base_t getBestState() { return BestState; }
2334  static constexpr base_t
2335  getBestState(const IncIntegerState<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> &) {
2336  return getBestState();
2337  }
2338 
2339  /// Take minimum of assumed and \p Value.
2340  IncIntegerState &takeAssumedMinimum(base_t Value) {
2341  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2342  this->Assumed = std::max(std::min(this->Assumed, Value), this->Known);
2343  return *this;
2344  }
2345 
2346  /// Take maximum of known and \p Value.
2347  IncIntegerState &takeKnownMaximum(base_t Value) {
2348  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2349  this->Assumed = std::max(Value, this->Assumed);
2350  this->Known = std::max(Value, this->Known);
2351  return *this;
2352  }
2353 
2354 private:
2355  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2356  takeAssumedMinimum(Value);
2357  }
2358  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override { takeKnownMaximum(Value); }
2359  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2360  this->Known = std::max(this->Known, KnownValue);
2361  this->Assumed = std::max(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2362  }
2363  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2364  this->Known = std::min(this->Known, KnownValue);
2365  this->Assumed = std::min(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2366  }
2367 };
2368 
2369 /// Specialization of the integer state for a decreasing value, hence 0 is the
2370 /// best state and ~0u the worst.
2371 template <typename base_ty = uint32_t>
2372 struct DecIntegerState : public IntegerStateBase<base_ty, 0, ~base_ty(0)> {
2373  using base_t = base_ty;
2374 
2375  /// Take maximum of assumed and \p Value.
2376  DecIntegerState &takeAssumedMaximum(base_t Value) {
2377  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2378  this->Assumed = std::min(std::max(this->Assumed, Value), this->Known);
2379  return *this;
2380  }
2381 
2382  /// Take minimum of known and \p Value.
2383  DecIntegerState &takeKnownMinimum(base_t Value) {
2384  // Make sure we never loose "known value".
2385  this->Assumed = std::min(Value, this->Assumed);
2386  this->Known = std::min(Value, this->Known);
2387  return *this;
2388  }
2389 
2390 private:
2391  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2392  takeAssumedMaximum(Value);
2393  }
2394  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override { takeKnownMinimum(Value); }
2395  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2396  this->Assumed = std::min(this->Assumed, KnownValue);
2397  this->Assumed = std::min(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2398  }
2399  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2400  this->Assumed = std::max(this->Assumed, KnownValue);
2401  this->Assumed = std::max(this->Assumed, AssumedValue);
2402  }
2403 };
2404 
2405 /// Simple wrapper for a single bit (boolean) state.
2406 struct BooleanState : public IntegerStateBase<bool, true, false> {
2407  using super = IntegerStateBase<bool, true, false>;
2408  using base_t = IntegerStateBase::base_t;
2409 
2410  BooleanState() = default;
2411  BooleanState(base_t Assumed) : super(Assumed) {}
2412 
2413  /// Set the assumed value to \p Value but never below the known one.
2414  void setAssumed(bool Value) { Assumed &= (Known | Value); }
2415 
2416  /// Set the known and asssumed value to \p Value.
2417  void setKnown(bool Value) {
2418  Known |= Value;
2419  Assumed |= Value;
2420  }
2421 
2422  /// Return true if the state is assumed to hold.
2423  bool isAssumed() const { return getAssumed(); }
2424 
2425  /// Return true if the state is known to hold.
2426  bool isKnown() const { return getKnown(); }
2427 
2428 private:
2429  void handleNewAssumedValue(base_t Value) override {
2430  if (!Value)
2431  Assumed = Known;
2432  }
2433  void handleNewKnownValue(base_t Value) override {
2434  if (Value)
2435  Known = (Assumed = Value);
2436  }
2437  void joinOR(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2438  Known |= KnownValue;
2439  Assumed |= AssumedValue;
2440  }
2441  void joinAND(base_t AssumedValue, base_t KnownValue) override {
2442  Known &= KnownValue;
2443  Assumed &= AssumedValue;
2444  }
2445 };
2446 
2447 /// State for an integer range.
2448 struct IntegerRangeState : public AbstractState {
2449 
2450  /// Bitwidth of the associated value.
2451  uint32_t BitWidth;
2452 
2453  /// State representing assumed range, initially set to empty.
2454  ConstantRange Assumed;
2455 
2456  /// State representing known range, initially set to [-inf, inf].
2457  ConstantRange Known;
2458 
2459  IntegerRangeState(uint32_t BitWidth)
2460  : BitWidth(BitWidth), Assumed(ConstantRange::getEmpty(BitWidth)),
2461  Known(ConstantRange::getFull(BitWidth)) {}
2462 
2463  IntegerRangeState(const ConstantRange &CR)
2464  : BitWidth(CR.getBitWidth()), Assumed(CR),
2465  Known(getWorstState(CR.getBitWidth())) {}
2466 
2467  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
2468  static ConstantRange getWorstState(uint32_t BitWidth) {
2469  return ConstantRange::getFull(BitWidth);
2470  }
2471 
2472  /// Return the best possible representable state.
2473  static ConstantRange getBestState(uint32_t BitWidth) {
2474  return ConstantRange::getEmpty(BitWidth);
2475  }
2476  static ConstantRange getBestState(const IntegerRangeState &IRS) {
2477  return getBestState(IRS.getBitWidth());
2478  }
2479 
2480  /// Return associated values' bit width.
2481  uint32_t getBitWidth() const { return BitWidth; }
2482 
2483  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
2484  bool isValidState() const override {
2485  return BitWidth > 0 && !Assumed.isFullSet();
2486  }
2487 
2488  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
2489  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return Assumed == Known; }
2490 
2491  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
2492  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
2493  Known = Assumed;
2494  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2495  }
2496 
2497  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
2498  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
2499  Assumed = Known;
2500  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2501  }
2502 
2503  /// Return the known state encoding
2504  ConstantRange getKnown() const { return Known; }
2505 
2506  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
2507  ConstantRange getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
2508 
2509  /// Unite assumed range with the passed state.
2510  void unionAssumed(const ConstantRange &R) {
2511  // Don't loose a known range.
2512  Assumed = Assumed.unionWith(R).intersectWith(Known);
2513  }
2514 
2515  /// See IntegerRangeState::unionAssumed(..).
2516  void unionAssumed(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2517  unionAssumed(R.getAssumed());
2518  }
2519 
2520  /// Unite known range with the passed state.
2521  void unionKnown(const ConstantRange &R) {
2522  // Don't loose a known range.
2523  Known = Known.unionWith(R);
2524  Assumed = Assumed.unionWith(Known);
2525  }
2526 
2527  /// See IntegerRangeState::unionKnown(..).
2528  void unionKnown(const IntegerRangeState &R) { unionKnown(R.getKnown()); }
2529 
2530  /// Intersect known range with the passed state.
2531  void intersectKnown(const ConstantRange &R) {
2532  Assumed = Assumed.intersectWith(R);
2533  Known = Known.intersectWith(R);
2534  }
2535 
2536  /// See IntegerRangeState::intersectKnown(..).
2537  void intersectKnown(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2538  intersectKnown(R.getKnown());
2539  }
2540 
2541  /// Equality for IntegerRangeState.
2542  bool operator==(const IntegerRangeState &R) const {
2543  return getAssumed() == R.getAssumed() && getKnown() == R.getKnown();
2544  }
2545 
2546  /// "Clamp" this state with \p R. The result is subtype dependent but it is
2547  /// intended that only information assumed in both states will be assumed in
2548  /// this one afterwards.
2549  IntegerRangeState operator^=(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2550  // NOTE: `^=` operator seems like `intersect` but in this case, we need to
2551  // take `union`.
2552  unionAssumed(R);
2553  return *this;
2554  }
2555 
2556  IntegerRangeState operator&=(const IntegerRangeState &R) {
2557  // NOTE: `&=` operator seems like `intersect` but in this case, we need to
2558  // take `union`.
2559  unionKnown(R);
2560  unionAssumed(R);
2561  return *this;
2562  }
2563 };
2564 
2565 /// Simple state for a set.
2566 ///
2567 /// This represents a state containing a set of values. The interface supports
2568 /// modelling sets that contain all possible elements. The state's internal
2569 /// value is modified using union or intersection operations.
2570 template <typename BaseTy> struct SetState : public AbstractState {
2571  /// A wrapper around a set that has semantics for handling unions and
2572  /// intersections with a "universal" set that contains all elements.
2573  struct SetContents {
2574  /// Creates a universal set with no concrete elements or an empty set.
2575  SetContents(bool Universal) : Universal(Universal) {}
2576 
2577  /// Creates a non-universal set with concrete values.
2578  SetContents(const DenseSet<BaseTy> &Assumptions)
2579  : Universal(false), Set(Assumptions) {}
2580 
2581  SetContents(bool Universal, const DenseSet<BaseTy> &Assumptions)
2582  : Universal(Universal), Set(Assumptions) {}
2583 
2584  const DenseSet<BaseTy> &getSet() const { return Set; }
2585 
2586  bool isUniversal() const { return Universal; }
2587 
2588  bool empty() const { return Set.empty() && !Universal; }
2589 
2590  /// Finds A := A ^ B where A or B could be the "Universal" set which
2591  /// contains every possible attribute. Returns true if changes were made.
2592  bool getIntersection(const SetContents &RHS) {
2593  bool IsUniversal = Universal;
2594  unsigned Size = Set.size();
2595 
2596  // A := A ^ U = A
2597  if (RHS.isUniversal())
2598  return false;
2599 
2600  // A := U ^ B = B
2601  if (Universal)
2602  Set = RHS.getSet();
2603  else
2604  set_intersect(Set, RHS.getSet());
2605 
2606  Universal &= RHS.isUniversal();
2607  return IsUniversal != Universal || Size != Set.size();
2608  }
2609 
2610  /// Finds A := A u B where A or B could be the "Universal" set which
2611  /// contains every possible attribute. returns true if changes were made.
2612  bool getUnion(const SetContents &RHS) {
2613  bool IsUniversal = Universal;
2614  unsigned Size = Set.size();
2615 
2616  // A := A u U = U = U u B
2617  if (!RHS.isUniversal() && !Universal)
2618  set_union(Set, RHS.getSet());
2619 
2620  Universal |= RHS.isUniversal();
2621  return IsUniversal != Universal || Size != Set.size();
2622  }
2623 
2624  private:
2625  /// Indicates if this set is "universal", containing every possible element.
2626  bool Universal;
2627 
2628  /// The set of currently active assumptions.
2629  DenseSet<BaseTy> Set;
2630  };
2631 
2632  SetState() : Known(false), Assumed(true), IsAtFixedpoint(false) {}
2633 
2634  /// Initializes the known state with an initial set and initializes the
2635  /// assumed state as universal.
2636  SetState(const DenseSet<BaseTy> &Known)
2637  : Known(Known), Assumed(true), IsAtFixedpoint(false) {}
2638 
2639  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
2640  bool isValidState() const override { return !Assumed.empty(); }
2641 
2642  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
2643  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return IsAtFixedpoint; }
2644 
2645  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
2646  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
2647  IsAtFixedpoint = true;
2648  Known = Assumed;
2649  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2650  }
2651 
2652  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
2653  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
2654  IsAtFixedpoint = true;
2655  Assumed = Known;
2656  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2657  }
2658 
2659  /// Return the known state encoding.
2660  const SetContents &getKnown() const { return Known; }
2661 
2662  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
2663  const SetContents &getAssumed() const { return Assumed; }
2664 
2665  /// Returns if the set state contains the element.
2666  bool setContains(const BaseTy &Elem) const {
2667  return Assumed.getSet().contains(Elem) || Known.getSet().contains(Elem);
2668  }
2669 
2670  /// Performs the set intersection between this set and \p RHS. Returns true if
2671  /// changes were made.
2672  bool getIntersection(const SetContents &RHS) {
2673  unsigned SizeBefore = Assumed.getSet().size();
2674 
2675  // Get intersection and make sure that the known set is still a proper
2676  // subset of the assumed set. A := K u (A ^ R).
2677  Assumed.getIntersection(RHS);
2678  Assumed.getUnion(Known);
2679 
2680  return SizeBefore != Assumed.getSet().size();
2681  }
2682 
2683  /// Performs the set union between this set and \p RHS. Returns true if
2684  /// changes were made.
2685  bool getUnion(const SetContents &RHS) { return Assumed.getUnion(RHS); }
2686 
2687 private:
2688  /// The set of values known for this state.
2689  SetContents Known;
2690 
2691  /// The set of assumed values for this state.
2692  SetContents Assumed;
2693 
2694  bool IsAtFixedpoint;
2695 };
2696 
2697 /// Helper struct necessary as the modular build fails if the virtual method
2698 /// IRAttribute::manifest is defined in the Attributor.cpp.
2699 struct IRAttributeManifest {
2700  static ChangeStatus manifestAttrs(Attributor &A, const IRPosition &IRP,
2701  const ArrayRef<Attribute> &DeducedAttrs,
2702  bool ForceReplace = false);
2703 };

2705 /// Helper to tie a abstract state implementation to an abstract attribute.
2706 template <typename StateTy, typename BaseType, class... Ts>
2707 struct StateWrapper : public BaseType, public StateTy {
2708  /// Provide static access to the type of the state.
2709  using StateType = StateTy;
2710 
2711  StateWrapper(const IRPosition &IRP, Ts... Args)
2712  : BaseType(IRP), StateTy(Args...) {}
2713 
2714  /// See AbstractAttribute::getState(...).
2715  StateType &getState() override { return *this; }
2716 
2717  /// See AbstractAttribute::getState(...).
2718  const StateType &getState() const override { return *this; }
2719 };

2721 /// Helper class that provides common functionality to manifest IR attributes.
2722 template <Attribute::AttrKind AK, typename BaseType>
2723 struct IRAttribute : public BaseType {
2724  IRAttribute(const IRPosition &IRP) : BaseType(IRP) {}
2725 
2726  /// See AbstractAttribute::initialize(...).
2727  virtual void initialize(Attributor &A) override {
2728  const IRPosition &IRP = this->getIRPosition();
2729  if (isa<UndefValue>(IRP.getAssociatedValue()) ||
2730  this->hasAttr(getAttrKind(), /* IgnoreSubsumingPositions */ false,
2731  &A)) {
2732  this->getState().indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
2733  return;
2734  }
2735 
2736  bool IsFnInterface = IRP.isFnInterfaceKind();
2737  const Function *FnScope = IRP.getAnchorScope();
2738  // TODO: Not all attributes require an exact definition. Find a way to
2739  // enable deduction for some but not all attributes in case the
2740  // definition might be changed at runtime, see also
2741  // http://lists.llvm.org/pipermail/llvm-dev/2018-February/121275.html.
2742  // TODO: We could always determine abstract attributes and if sufficient
2743  // information was found we could duplicate the functions that do not
2744  // have an exact definition.
2745  if (IsFnInterface && (!FnScope || !A.isFunctionIPOAmendable(*FnScope)))
2746  this->getState().indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
2747  }
2748 
2749  /// See AbstractAttribute::manifest(...).
2750  ChangeStatus manifest(Attributor &A) override {
2751  if (isa<UndefValue>(this->getIRPosition().getAssociatedValue()))
2752  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2753  SmallVector<Attribute, 4> DeducedAttrs;
2754  getDeducedAttributes(this->getAnchorValue().getContext(), DeducedAttrs);
2755  return IRAttributeManifest::manifestAttrs(A, this->getIRPosition(),
2756  DeducedAttrs);
2757  }
2758 
2759  /// Return the kind that identifies the abstract attribute implementation.
2760  Attribute::AttrKind getAttrKind() const { return AK; }
2761 
2762  /// Return the deduced attributes in \p Attrs.
2763  virtual void getDeducedAttributes(LLVMContext &Ctx,
2764  SmallVectorImpl<Attribute> &Attrs) const {
2765  Attrs.emplace_back(Attribute::get(Ctx, getAttrKind()));
2766  }
2767 };
2768 
2769 /// Base struct for all "concrete attribute" deductions.
2770 ///
2771 /// The abstract attribute is a minimal interface that allows the Attributor to
2772 /// orchestrate the abstract/fixpoint analysis. The design allows to hide away
2773 /// implementation choices made for the subclasses but also to structure their
2774 /// implementation and simplify the use of other abstract attributes in-flight.
2775 ///
2776 /// To allow easy creation of new attributes, most methods have default
2777 /// implementations. The ones that do not are generally straight forward, except
2778 /// `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl` which is the location of most reasoning
2779 /// associated with the abstract attribute. The update is invoked by the
2780 /// Attributor in case the situation used to justify the current optimistic
2781 /// state might have changed. The Attributor determines this automatically
2782 /// by monitoring the `Attributor::getAAFor` calls made by abstract attributes.
2783 ///
2784 /// The `updateImpl` method should inspect the IR and other abstract attributes
2785 /// in-flight to justify the best possible (=optimistic) state. The actual
2786 /// implementation is, similar to the underlying abstract state encoding, not
2787 /// exposed. In the most common case, the `updateImpl` will go through a list of
2788 /// reasons why its optimistic state is valid given the current information. If
2789 /// any combination of them holds and is sufficient to justify the current
2790 /// optimistic state, the method shall return UNCHAGED. If not, the optimistic
2791 /// state is adjusted to the situation and the method shall return CHANGED.
2792 ///
2793 /// If the manifestation of the "concrete attribute" deduced by the subclass
2794 /// differs from the "default" behavior, which is a (set of) LLVM-IR
2795 /// attribute(s) for an argument, call site argument, function return value, or
2796 /// function, the `AbstractAttribute::manifest` method should be overloaded.
2797 ///
2798 /// NOTE: If the state obtained via getState() is INVALID, thus if
2799 /// AbstractAttribute::getState().isValidState() returns false, no
2800 /// information provided by the methods of this class should be used.
2801 /// NOTE: The Attributor currently has certain limitations to what we can do.
2802 /// As a general rule of thumb, "concrete" abstract attributes should *for
2803 /// now* only perform "backward" information propagation. That means
2804 /// optimistic information obtained through abstract attributes should
2805 /// only be used at positions that precede the origin of the information
2806 /// with regards to the program flow. More practically, information can
2807 /// *now* be propagated from instructions to their enclosing function, but
2808 /// *not* from call sites to the called function. The mechanisms to allow
2809 /// both directions will be added in the future.
2810 /// NOTE: The mechanics of adding a new "concrete" abstract attribute are
2811 /// described in the file comment.
2812 struct AbstractAttribute : public IRPosition, public AADepGraphNode {
2813  using StateType = AbstractState;
2814 
2815  AbstractAttribute(const IRPosition &IRP) : IRPosition(IRP) {}
2816 
2817  /// Virtual destructor.
2818  virtual ~AbstractAttribute() = default;
2819 
2820  /// This function is used to identify if an \p DGN is of type
2821  /// AbstractAttribute so that the dyn_cast and cast can use such information
2822  /// to cast an AADepGraphNode to an AbstractAttribute.
2823  ///
2824  /// We eagerly return true here because all AADepGraphNodes except for the
2825  /// Synthethis Node are of type AbstractAttribute
2826  static bool classof(const AADepGraphNode *DGN) { return true; }
2827 
2828  /// Initialize the state with the information in the Attributor \p A.
2829  ///
2830  /// This function is called by the Attributor once all abstract attributes
2831  /// have been identified. It can and shall be used for task like:
2832  /// - identify existing knowledge in the IR and use it for the "known state"
2833  /// - perform any work that is not going to change over time, e.g., determine
2834  /// a subset of the IR, or attributes in-flight, that have to be looked at
2835  /// in the `updateImpl` method.
2836  virtual void initialize(Attributor &A) {}
2837 
2838  /// A query AA is always scheduled as long as we do updates because it does
2839  /// lazy computation that cannot be determined to be done from the outside.
2840  /// However, while query AAs will not be fixed if they do not have outstanding
2841  /// dependences, we will only schedule them like other AAs. If a query AA that
2842  /// received a new query it needs to request an update via
2843  /// `Attributor::requestUpdateForAA`.
2844  virtual bool isQueryAA() const { return false; }
2845 
2846  /// Return the internal abstract state for inspection.
2847  virtual StateType &getState() = 0;
2848  virtual const StateType &getState() const = 0;
2849 
2850  /// Return an IR position, see struct IRPosition.
2851  const IRPosition &getIRPosition() const { return *this; };
2852  IRPosition &getIRPosition() { return *this; };
2853 
2854  /// Helper functions, for debug purposes only.
2855  ///{
2856  void print(raw_ostream &OS) const override;
2857  virtual void printWithDeps(raw_ostream &OS) const;
2858  void dump() const { print(dbgs()); }
2859 
2860  /// This function should return the "summarized" assumed state as string.
2861  virtual const std::string getAsStr() const = 0;
2862 
2863  /// This function should return the name of the AbstractAttribute
2864  virtual const std::string getName() const = 0;
2865 
2866  /// This function should return the address of the ID of the AbstractAttribute
2867  virtual const char *getIdAddr() const = 0;
2868  ///}
2869 
2870  /// Allow the Attributor access to the protected methods.
2871  friend struct Attributor;
2872 
2873 protected:
2874  /// Hook for the Attributor to trigger an update of the internal state.
2875  ///
2876  /// If this attribute is already fixed, this method will return UNCHANGED,
2877  /// otherwise it delegates to `AbstractAttribute::updateImpl`.
2878  ///
2879  /// \Return CHANGED if the internal state changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
2880  ChangeStatus update(Attributor &A);
2881 
2882  /// Hook for the Attributor to trigger the manifestation of the information
2883  /// represented by the abstract attribute in the LLVM-IR.
2884  ///
2885  /// \Return CHANGED if the IR was altered, otherwise UNCHANGED.
2886  virtual ChangeStatus manifest(Attributor &A) {
2887  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
2888  }
2889 
2890  /// Hook to enable custom statistic tracking, called after manifest that
2891  /// resulted in a change if statistics are enabled.
2892  ///
2893  /// We require subclasses to provide an implementation so we remember to
2894  /// add statistics for them.
2895  virtual void trackStatistics() const = 0;
2896 
2897  /// The actual update/transfer function which has to be implemented by the
2898  /// derived classes.
2899  ///
2900  /// If it is called, the environment has changed and we have to determine if
2901  /// the current information is still valid or adjust it otherwise.
2902  ///
2903  /// \Return CHANGED if the internal state changed, otherwise UNCHANGED.
2904  virtual ChangeStatus updateImpl(Attributor &A) = 0;
2905 };
2906 
2907 /// Forward declarations of output streams for debug purposes.
2908 ///
2909 ///{
2910 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const AbstractAttribute &AA);
2911 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, ChangeStatus S);
2912 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, IRPosition::Kind);
2913 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const IRPosition &);
2914 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const AbstractState &State);
2915 template <typename base_ty, base_ty BestState, base_ty WorstState>
2916 raw_ostream &
2917 operator<<(raw_ostream &OS,
2918  const IntegerStateBase<base_ty, BestState, WorstState> &S) {
2919  return OS << "(" << S.getKnown() << "-" << S.getAssumed() << ")"
2920  << static_cast<const AbstractState &>(S);
2921 }
2922 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS, const IntegerRangeState &State);

2925 struct AttributorPass : public PassInfoMixin<AttributorPass> {
2926  PreservedAnalyses run(Module &M, ModuleAnalysisManager &AM);
2927 };
2928 struct AttributorCGSCCPass : public PassInfoMixin<AttributorCGSCCPass> {
2929  PreservedAnalyses run(LazyCallGraph::SCC &C, CGSCCAnalysisManager &AM,

2936 /// Helper function to clamp a state \p S of type \p StateType with the
2937 /// information in \p R and indicate/return if \p S did change (as-in update is
2938 /// required to be run again).
2939 template <typename StateType>
2940 ChangeStatus clampStateAndIndicateChange(StateType &S, const StateType &R) {
2941  auto Assumed = S.getAssumed();
2942  S ^= R;
2943  return Assumed == S.getAssumed() ? ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED
2944  : ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
2945 }

3196 /// An abstract interface to determine reachability of point A to B.
3197 struct AAReachability : public StateWrapper<BooleanState, AbstractAttribute> {
3198  using Base = StateWrapper<BooleanState, AbstractAttribute>;
3199  AAReachability(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : Base(IRP) {}
3200 
3201  /// Returns true if 'From' instruction is assumed to reach, 'To' instruction.
3202  /// Users should provide two positions they are interested in, and the class
3203  /// determines (and caches) reachability.
3204  bool isAssumedReachable(Attributor &A, const Instruction &From,
3205  const Instruction &To) const {
3206  if (!getState().isValidState())
3207  return true;
3208  return A.getInfoCache().getPotentiallyReachable(From, To);
3209  }
3210 
3211  /// Returns true if 'From' instruction is known to reach, 'To' instruction.
3212  /// Users should provide two positions they are interested in, and the class
3213  /// determines (and caches) reachability.
3214  bool isKnownReachable(Attributor &A, const Instruction &From,
3215  const Instruction &To) const {
3216  if (!getState().isValidState())
3217  return false;
3218  return A.getInfoCache().getPotentiallyReachable(From, To);
3219  }
3220 
3221  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
3222  static AAReachability &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
3223  Attributor &A);
3224 
3225  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
3226  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAReachability"; }
3227 
3228  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()

3232  /// AAReachability
3233  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
3234  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
3235  }
3236 
3237  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)

3331 /// An abstract interface for liveness abstract attribute.
3332 struct AAIsDead
3333  : public StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint8_t, 3, 0>, AbstractAttribute> {
3334  using Base = StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint8_t, 3, 0>, AbstractAttribute>;
3335  AAIsDead(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : Base(IRP) {}
3336 
3337  /// State encoding bits. A set bit in the state means the property holds.
3338  enum {
3339  HAS_NO_EFFECT = 1 << 0,
3340  IS_REMOVABLE = 1 << 1,
3341 
3342  IS_DEAD = HAS_NO_EFFECT | IS_REMOVABLE,
3343  };
3344  static_assert(IS_DEAD == getBestState(), "Unexpected BEST_STATE value");
3345 
3346 protected:
3347  /// The query functions are protected such that other attributes need to go
3348  /// through the Attributor interfaces: `Attributor::isAssumedDead(...)`
3349 
3350  /// Returns true if the underlying value is assumed dead.
3351  virtual bool isAssumedDead() const = 0;
3352 
3353  /// Returns true if the underlying value is known dead.
3354  virtual bool isKnownDead() const = 0;
3355 
3356  /// Returns true if \p BB is assumed dead.
3357  virtual bool isAssumedDead(const BasicBlock *BB) const = 0;
3358 
3359  /// Returns true if \p BB is known dead.
3360  virtual bool isKnownDead(const BasicBlock *BB) const = 0;
3361 
3362  /// Returns true if \p I is assumed dead.
3363  virtual bool isAssumedDead(const Instruction *I) const = 0;
3364 
3365  /// Returns true if \p I is known dead.
3366  virtual bool isKnownDead(const Instruction *I) const = 0;
3367 
3368  /// This method is used to check if at least one instruction in a collection
3369  /// of instructions is live.
3370  template <typename T> bool isLiveInstSet(T begin, T end) const {
3371  for (const auto &I : llvm::make_range(begin, end)) {
3372  assert(I->getFunction() == getIRPosition().getAssociatedFunction() &&
3373  "Instruction must be in the same anchor scope function.");
3374 
3375  if (!isAssumedDead(I))
3376  return true;
3377  }
3378 
3379  return false;
3380  }
3381 
3382 public:
3383  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
3384  static AAIsDead &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A);
3385 
3386  /// Determine if \p F might catch asynchronous exceptions.
3387  static bool mayCatchAsynchronousExceptions(const Function &F) {
3388  return F.hasPersonalityFn() && !canSimplifyInvokeNoUnwind(&F);
3389  }
3390 
3391  /// Return if the edge from \p From BB to \p To BB is assumed dead.
3392  /// This is specifically useful in AAReachability.
3393  virtual bool isEdgeDead(const BasicBlock *From, const BasicBlock *To) const {
3394  return false;
3395  }
3396 
3397  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
3398  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAIsDead"; }
3399 
3400  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
3401  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
3402 
3403  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is AAIsDead
3404  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
3405  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
3406  }
3407 
3408  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
3409  static const char ID;
3410 
3411  friend struct Attributor;
3412 };
3413 
3414 /// State for dereferenceable attribute
3415 struct DerefState : AbstractState {
3416 
3417  static DerefState getBestState() { return DerefState(); }
3418  static DerefState getBestState(const DerefState &) { return getBestState(); }
3419 
3420  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
3421  static DerefState getWorstState() {
3422  DerefState DS;
3423  DS.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3424  return DS;
3425  }
3426  static DerefState getWorstState(const DerefState &) {
3427  return getWorstState();
3428  }
3429 
3430  /// State representing for dereferenceable bytes.
3431  IncIntegerState<> DerefBytesState;
3432 
3433  /// Map representing for accessed memory offsets and sizes.
3434  /// A key is Offset and a value is size.
3435  /// If there is a load/store instruction something like,
3436  /// p[offset] = v;
3437  /// (offset, sizeof(v)) will be inserted to this map.
3438  /// std::map is used because we want to iterate keys in ascending order.
3439  std::map<int64_t, uint64_t> AccessedBytesMap;
3440 
3441  /// Helper function to calculate dereferenceable bytes from current known
3442  /// bytes and accessed bytes.
3443  ///
3444  /// int f(int *A){
3445  /// *A = 0;
3446  /// *(A+2) = 2;
3447  /// *(A+1) = 1;
3448  /// *(A+10) = 10;
3449  /// }
3450  /// ```
3451  /// In that case, AccessedBytesMap is `{0:4, 4:4, 8:4, 40:4}`.
3452  /// AccessedBytesMap is std::map so it is iterated in accending order on
3453  /// key(Offset). So KnownBytes will be updated like this:
3454  ///
3455  /// |Access | KnownBytes
3456  /// |(0, 4)| 0 -> 4
3457  /// |(4, 4)| 4 -> 8
3458  /// |(8, 4)| 8 -> 12
3459  /// |(40, 4) | 12 (break)
3460  void computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap() {
3461  int64_t KnownBytes = DerefBytesState.getKnown();
3462  for (auto &Access : AccessedBytesMap) {
3463  if (KnownBytes < Access.first)
3464  break;
3465  KnownBytes = std::max(KnownBytes, Access.first + (int64_t)Access.second);
3466  }
3467 
3468  DerefBytesState.takeKnownMaximum(KnownBytes);
3469  }
3470 
3471  /// State representing that whether the value is globaly dereferenceable.
3472  BooleanState GlobalState;
3473 
3474  /// See AbstractState::isValidState()
3475  bool isValidState() const override { return DerefBytesState.isValidState(); }
3476 
3477  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint()
3478  bool isAtFixpoint() const override {
3479  return !isValidState() ||
3480  (DerefBytesState.isAtFixpoint() && GlobalState.isAtFixpoint());
3481  }
3482 
3483  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
3484  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
3485  DerefBytesState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
3486  GlobalState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
3487  return ChangeStatus::UNCHANGED;
3488  }
3489 
3490  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
3491  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
3492  DerefBytesState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3493  GlobalState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3494  return ChangeStatus::CHANGED;
3495  }
3496 
3497  /// Update known dereferenceable bytes.
3498  void takeKnownDerefBytesMaximum(uint64_t Bytes) {
3499  DerefBytesState.takeKnownMaximum(Bytes);
3500 
3501  // Known bytes might increase.
3502  computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap();
3503  }
3504 
3505  /// Update assumed dereferenceable bytes.
3506  void takeAssumedDerefBytesMinimum(uint64_t Bytes) {
3507  DerefBytesState.takeAssumedMinimum(Bytes);
3508  }
3509 
3510  /// Add accessed bytes to the map.
3511  void addAccessedBytes(int64_t Offset, uint64_t Size) {
3512  uint64_t &AccessedBytes = AccessedBytesMap[Offset];
3513  AccessedBytes = std::max(AccessedBytes, Size);
3514 
3515  // Known bytes might increase.
3516  computeKnownDerefBytesFromAccessedMap();
3517  }
3518 
3519  /// Equality for DerefState.
3520  bool operator==(const DerefState &R) const {
3521  return this->DerefBytesState == R.DerefBytesState &&
3522  this->GlobalState == R.GlobalState;
3523  }
3524 
3525  /// Inequality for DerefState.
3526  bool operator!=(const DerefState &R) const { return !(*this == R); }
3527 
3528  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator^=
3529  DerefState operator^=(const DerefState &R) {
3530  DerefBytesState ^= R.DerefBytesState;
3531  GlobalState ^= R.GlobalState;
3532  return *this;
3533  }
3534 
3535  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator+=
3536  DerefState operator+=(const DerefState &R) {
3537  DerefBytesState += R.DerefBytesState;
3538  GlobalState += R.GlobalState;
3539  return *this;
3540  }
3541 
3542  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator&=
3543  DerefState operator&=(const DerefState &R) {
3544  DerefBytesState &= R.DerefBytesState;
3545  GlobalState &= R.GlobalState;
3546  return *this;
3547  }
3548 
3549  /// See IntegerStateBase::operator|=
3550  DerefState operator|=(const DerefState &R) {
3551  DerefBytesState |= R.DerefBytesState;
3552  GlobalState |= R.GlobalState;
3553  return *this;
3554  }
3555 
3556 protected:
3557  const AANonNull *NonNullAA = nullptr;
3558 };

3646 /// An abstract interface for all nocapture attributes.
3647 struct AANoCapture
3648  : public IRAttribute<
3649  Attribute::NoCapture,
3650  StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint16_t, 7, 0>, AbstractAttribute>> {
3651  AANoCapture(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : IRAttribute(IRP) {}
3652 
3653  /// State encoding bits. A set bit in the state means the property holds.
3654  /// NO_CAPTURE is the best possible state, 0 the worst possible state.
3655  enum {
3656  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_MEM = 1 << 0,
3657  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_INT = 1 << 1,
3658  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_RET = 1 << 2,
3659 
3660  /// If we do not capture the value in memory or through integers we can only
3661  /// communicate it back as a derived pointer.
3662  NO_CAPTURE_MAYBE_RETURNED = NOT_CAPTURED_IN_MEM | NOT_CAPTURED_IN_INT,
3663 
3664  /// If we do not capture the value in memory, through integers, or as a
3665  /// derived pointer we know it is not captured.
3666  NO_CAPTURE =
3667  NOT_CAPTURED_IN_MEM | NOT_CAPTURED_IN_INT | NOT_CAPTURED_IN_RET,
3668  };
3669 
3670  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not captured in its
3671  /// respective scope.
3672  bool isKnownNoCapture() const { return isKnown(NO_CAPTURE); }
3673 
3674  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not captured in its
3675  /// respective scope.
3676  bool isAssumedNoCapture() const { return isAssumed(NO_CAPTURE); }
3677 
3678  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not captured in its
3679  /// respective scope but we allow it to escape through a "return".
3680  bool isKnownNoCaptureMaybeReturned() const {
3681  return isKnown(NO_CAPTURE_MAYBE_RETURNED);
3682  }
3683 
3684  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not captured in its
3685  /// respective scope but we allow it to escape through a "return".
3686  bool isAssumedNoCaptureMaybeReturned() const {
3687  return isAssumed(NO_CAPTURE_MAYBE_RETURNED);
3688  }
3689 
3690  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
3691  static AANoCapture &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A);
3692 
3693  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
3694  const std::string getName() const override { return "AANoCapture"; }
3695 
3696  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
3697  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
3698 
3699  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is AANoCapture
3700  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
3701  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
3702  }
3703 
3704  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
3705  static const char ID;

3708 struct ValueSimplifyStateType : public AbstractState {
3709 
3710  ValueSimplifyStateType(Type *Ty) : Ty(Ty) {}
3711 
3712  static ValueSimplifyStateType getBestState(Type *Ty) {
3713  return ValueSimplifyStateType(Ty);
3714  }
3715  static ValueSimplifyStateType getBestState(const ValueSimplifyStateType &VS) {
3716  return getBestState(VS.Ty);
3717  }
3718 
3719  /// Return the worst possible representable state.
3720  static ValueSimplifyStateType getWorstState(Type *Ty) {
3721  ValueSimplifyStateType DS(Ty);
3722  DS.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3723  return DS;
3724  }
3725  static ValueSimplifyStateType
3726  getWorstState(const ValueSimplifyStateType &VS) {
3727  return getWorstState(VS.Ty);
3728  }
3729 
3730  /// See AbstractState::isValidState(...)
3731  bool isValidState() const override { return BS.isValidState(); }
3732 
3733  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint(...)
3734  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return BS.isAtFixpoint(); }
3735 
3736  /// Return the assumed state encoding.
3737  ValueSimplifyStateType getAssumed() { return *this; }
3738  const ValueSimplifyStateType &getAssumed() const { return *this; }
3739 
3740  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
3741  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
3742  return BS.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
3743  }
3744 
3745  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
3746  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
3747  return BS.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
3748  }
3749 
3750  /// "Clamp" this state with \p PVS.
3751  ValueSimplifyStateType operator^=(const ValueSimplifyStateType &VS) {
3752  BS ^= VS.BS;
3753  unionAssumed(VS.SimplifiedAssociatedValue);
3754  return *this;
3755  }
3756 
3757  bool operator==(const ValueSimplifyStateType &RHS) const {
3758  if (isValidState() != RHS.isValidState())
3759  return false;
3760  if (!isValidState() && !RHS.isValidState())
3761  return true;
3762  return SimplifiedAssociatedValue == RHS.SimplifiedAssociatedValue;
3763  }
3764 
3765 protected:
3766  /// The type of the original value.
3767  Type *Ty;
3768 
3769  /// Merge \p Other into the currently assumed simplified value
3770  bool unionAssumed(Optional<Value *> Other);
3771 
3772  /// Helper to track validity and fixpoint
3773  BooleanState BS;
3774 
3775  /// An assumed simplified value. Initially, it is set to Optional::None, which
3776  /// means that the value is not clear under current assumption. If in the
3777  /// pessimistic state, getAssumedSimplifiedValue doesn't return this value but
3778  /// returns orignal associated value.
3779  Optional<Value *> SimplifiedAssociatedValue;
3780 };

3848 /// An abstract interface for privatizability.
3849 ///
3850 /// A pointer is privatizable if it can be replaced by a new, private one.
3851 /// Privatizing pointer reduces the use count, interaction between unrelated
3852 /// code parts.
3853 ///
3854 /// In order for a pointer to be privatizable its value cannot be observed
3855 /// (=nocapture), it is (for now) not written (=readonly & noalias), we know
3856 /// what values are necessary to make the private copy look like the original
3857 /// one, and the values we need can be loaded (=dereferenceable).
3858 struct AAPrivatizablePtr
3859  : public StateWrapper<BooleanState, AbstractAttribute> {
3860  using Base = StateWrapper<BooleanState, AbstractAttribute>;
3861  AAPrivatizablePtr(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : Base(IRP) {}
3862 
3863  /// Returns true if pointer privatization is assumed to be possible.
3864  bool isAssumedPrivatizablePtr() const { return getAssumed(); }
3865 
3866  /// Returns true if pointer privatization is known to be possible.
3867  bool isKnownPrivatizablePtr() const { return getKnown(); }
3868 
3869  /// Return the type we can choose for a private copy of the underlying
3870  /// value. None means it is not clear yet, nullptr means there is none.
3871  virtual Optional<Type *> getPrivatizableType() const = 0;
3872 
3873  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
3874  static AAPrivatizablePtr &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
3875  Attributor &A);
3876 
3877  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
3878  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAPrivatizablePtr"; }
3879 
3880  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
3881  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
3882 
3883  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
3884  /// AAPricatizablePtr
3885  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
3886  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
3887  }
3888 
3889  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
3890  static const char ID;
3891 };

3893 /// An abstract interface for memory access kind related attributes

3895 struct AAMemoryBehavior

3899  AAMemoryBehavior(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : IRAttribute(IRP) {}
3900 
3901  /// State encoding bits. A set bit in the state means the property holds.
3902  /// BEST_STATE is the best possible state, 0 the worst possible state.
3903  enum {

3905  NO_WRITES = 1 << 1,

3913  /// in its respective scope.

3917  /// in its respective scope.
3918  bool isAssumedReadNone() const { return isAssumed(NO_ACCESSES); }
3919 
3920  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not accessed
3921  /// (=written) in its respective scope.
3922  bool isKnownReadOnly() const { return isKnown(NO_WRITES); }
3923 
3924  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not accessed
3925  /// (=written) in its respective scope.
3926  bool isAssumedReadOnly() const { return isAssumed(NO_WRITES); }
3927 
3928  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value is not read in its
3929  /// respective scope.
3930  bool isKnownWriteOnly() const { return isKnown(NO_READS); }
3931 
3932  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is not read in its
3933  /// respective scope.
3934  bool isAssumedWriteOnly() const { return isAssumed(NO_READS); }
3935 
3936  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
3937  static AAMemoryBehavior &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
3938  Attributor &A);
3939 
3940  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()

3942 
3943  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()

3945 
3946  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
3947  /// AAMemoryBehavior
3948  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
3949  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
3950  }
3951 
3952  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
3953  static const char ID;

3956 /// An abstract interface for all memory location attributes
3957 /// (readnone/argmemonly/inaccessiblememonly/inaccessibleorargmemonly).
3958 struct AAMemoryLocation
3959  : public IRAttribute<
3960  Attribute::ReadNone,
3961  StateWrapper<BitIntegerState<uint32_t, 511>, AbstractAttribute>> {
3962  using MemoryLocationsKind = StateType::base_t;
3963 
3964  AAMemoryLocation(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : IRAttribute(IRP) {}
3965 
3966  /// Encoding of different locations that could be accessed by a memory
3967  /// access.
3968  enum {
3969  ALL_LOCATIONS = 0,
3970  NO_LOCAL_MEM = 1 << 0,
3971  NO_CONST_MEM = 1 << 1,
3972  NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM = 1 << 2,
3973  NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM = 1 << 3,
3974  NO_GLOBAL_MEM = NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM | NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM,
3975  NO_ARGUMENT_MEM = 1 << 4,
3976  NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM = 1 << 5,
3977  NO_MALLOCED_MEM = 1 << 6,
3978  NO_UNKOWN_MEM = 1 << 7,
3979  NO_LOCATIONS = NO_LOCAL_MEM | NO_CONST_MEM | NO_GLOBAL_INTERNAL_MEM |
3980  NO_GLOBAL_EXTERNAL_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM |
3981  NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_MALLOCED_MEM | NO_UNKOWN_MEM,
3982 
3983  // Helper bit to track if we gave up or not.
3984  VALID_STATE = NO_LOCATIONS + 1,
3985 
3986  BEST_STATE = NO_LOCATIONS | VALID_STATE,
3987  };
3988  static_assert(BEST_STATE == getBestState(), "Unexpected BEST_STATE value");
3989 
3990  /// Return true if we know that the associated functions has no observable
3991  /// accesses.
3992  bool isKnownReadNone() const { return isKnown(NO_LOCATIONS); }
3993 
3994  /// Return true if we assume that the associated functions has no observable
3995  /// accesses.
3996  bool isAssumedReadNone() const {
3997  return isAssumed(NO_LOCATIONS) || isAssumedStackOnly();
3998  }
3999 
4000  /// Return true if we know that the associated functions has at most
4001  /// local/stack accesses.
4002  bool isKnowStackOnly() const {
4003  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_LOCAL_MEM, true, true));
4004  }
4005 
4006  /// Return true if we assume that the associated functions has at most
4007  /// local/stack accesses.
4008  bool isAssumedStackOnly() const {
4009  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_LOCAL_MEM, true, true));
4010  }
4011 
4012  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
4013  /// inaccesible memory only (see Attribute::InaccessibleMemOnly).
4014  bool isKnownInaccessibleMemOnly() const {
4015  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM, true, true));
4016  }
4017 
4018  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
4019  /// inaccesible memory only (see Attribute::InaccessibleMemOnly).
4020  bool isAssumedInaccessibleMemOnly() const {
4021  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM, true, true));
4022  }
4023 
4024  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
4025  /// argument pointees (see Attribute::ArgMemOnly).
4026  bool isKnownArgMemOnly() const {
4027  return isKnown(inverseLocation(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4028  }
4029 
4030  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
4031  /// argument pointees (see Attribute::ArgMemOnly).
4032  bool isAssumedArgMemOnly() const {
4033  return isAssumed(inverseLocation(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4034  }
4035 
4036  /// Return true if we know that the underlying value will only access
4037  /// inaccesible memory or argument pointees (see
4038  /// Attribute::InaccessibleOrArgMemOnly).
4039  bool isKnownInaccessibleOrArgMemOnly() const {
4040  return isKnown(
4041  inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4042  }
4043 
4044  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value will only access
4045  /// inaccesible memory or argument pointees (see
4046  /// Attribute::InaccessibleOrArgMemOnly).
4047  bool isAssumedInaccessibleOrArgMemOnly() const {
4048  return isAssumed(
4049  inverseLocation(NO_INACCESSIBLE_MEM | NO_ARGUMENT_MEM, true, true));
4050  }
4051 
4052  /// Return true if the underlying value may access memory through arguement
4053  /// pointers of the associated function, if any.
4054  bool mayAccessArgMem() const { return !isAssumed(NO_ARGUMENT_MEM); }
4055 
4056  /// Return true if only the memory locations specififed by \p MLK are assumed
4057  /// to be accessed by the associated function.
4058  bool isAssumedSpecifiedMemOnly(MemoryLocationsKind MLK) const {
4059  return isAssumed(MLK);
4060  }
4061 
4062  /// Return the locations that are assumed to be not accessed by the associated
4063  /// function, if any.
4064  MemoryLocationsKind getAssumedNotAccessedLocation() const {
4065  return getAssumed();
4066  }
4067 
4068  /// Return the inverse of location \p Loc, thus for NO_XXX the return
4069  /// describes ONLY_XXX. The flags \p AndLocalMem and \p AndConstMem determine
4070  /// if local (=stack) and constant memory are allowed as well. Most of the
4071  /// time we do want them to be included, e.g., argmemonly allows accesses via
4072  /// argument pointers or local or constant memory accesses.
4073  static MemoryLocationsKind
4074  inverseLocation(MemoryLocationsKind Loc, bool AndLocalMem, bool AndConstMem) {
4075  return NO_LOCATIONS & ~(Loc | (AndLocalMem ? NO_LOCAL_MEM : 0) |
4076  (AndConstMem ? NO_CONST_MEM : 0));
4077  };
4078 
4079  /// Return the locations encoded by \p MLK as a readable string.
4080  static std::string getMemoryLocationsAsStr(MemoryLocationsKind MLK);
4081 
4082  /// Simple enum to distinguish read/write/read-write accesses.
4083  enum AccessKind {
4084  NONE = 0,
4085  READ = 1 << 0,
4086  WRITE = 1 << 1,
4087  READ_WRITE = READ | WRITE,
4088  };
4089 
4090  /// Check \p Pred on all accesses to the memory kinds specified by \p MLK.
4091  ///
4092  /// This method will evaluate \p Pred on all accesses (access instruction +
4093  /// underlying accessed memory pointer) and it will return true if \p Pred
4094  /// holds every time.
4095  virtual bool checkForAllAccessesToMemoryKind(
4096  function_ref<bool(const Instruction *, const Value *, AccessKind,
4097  MemoryLocationsKind)>
4098  Pred,
4099  MemoryLocationsKind MLK) const = 0;
4100 
4101  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4102  static AAMemoryLocation &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4103  Attributor &A);
4104 
4105  /// See AbstractState::getAsStr().
4106  const std::string getAsStr() const override {
4107  return getMemoryLocationsAsStr(getAssumedNotAccessedLocation());
4108  }
4109 
4110  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4111  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAMemoryLocation"; }
4112 
4113  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4114  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4115 
4116  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4117  /// AAMemoryLocation
4118  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4119  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4120  }
4121 
4122  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4123  static const char ID;
4124 };

4127 struct AAValueConstantRange
4128  : public StateWrapper<IntegerRangeState, AbstractAttribute, uint32_t> {
4129  using Base = StateWrapper<IntegerRangeState, AbstractAttribute, uint32_t>;
4130  AAValueConstantRange(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A)
4131  : Base(IRP, IRP.getAssociatedType()->getIntegerBitWidth()) {}
4132 
4133  /// See AbstractAttribute::getState(...).
4134  IntegerRangeState &getState() override { return *this; }
4135  const IntegerRangeState &getState() const override { return *this; }
4136 
4137  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4138  static AAValueConstantRange &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4139  Attributor &A);
4140 
4141  /// Return an assumed range for the associated value a program point \p CtxI.
4142  /// If \p I is nullptr, simply return an assumed range.
4143  virtual ConstantRange
4144  getAssumedConstantRange(Attributor &A,
4145  const Instruction *CtxI = nullptr) const = 0;
4146 
4147  /// Return a known range for the associated value at a program point \p CtxI.
4148  /// If \p I is nullptr, simply return a known range.
4149  virtual ConstantRange
4150  getKnownConstantRange(Attributor &A,
4151  const Instruction *CtxI = nullptr) const = 0;
4152 
4153  /// Return an assumed constant for the associated value a program point \p
4154  /// CtxI.
4155  Optional<ConstantInt *>
4156  getAssumedConstantInt(Attributor &A,
4157  const Instruction *CtxI = nullptr) const {
4158  ConstantRange RangeV = getAssumedConstantRange(A, CtxI);
4159  if (auto *C = RangeV.getSingleElement())
4160  return cast<ConstantInt>(
4161  ConstantInt::get(getAssociatedValue().getType(), *C));
4162  if (RangeV.isEmptySet())
4163  return llvm::None;
4164  return nullptr;
4165  }
4166 
4167  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4168  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAValueConstantRange"; }
4169 
4170  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4171  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4172 
4173  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4174  /// AAValueConstantRange
4175  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4176  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4177  }
4178 
4179  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4180  static const char ID;
4181 };
4182 
4183 /// A class for a set state.
4184 /// The assumed boolean state indicates whether the corresponding set is full
4185 /// set or not. If the assumed state is false, this is the worst state. The
4186 /// worst state (invalid state) of set of potential values is when the set
4187 /// contains every possible value (i.e. we cannot in any way limit the value
4188 /// that the target position can take). That never happens naturally, we only
4189 /// force it. As for the conditions under which we force it, see
4190 /// AAPotentialValues.
4191 template <typename MemberTy, typename KeyInfo = DenseMapInfo<MemberTy>>
4192 struct PotentialValuesState : AbstractState {
4193  using SetTy = DenseSet<MemberTy, KeyInfo>;
4194 
4195  PotentialValuesState() : IsValidState(true), UndefIsContained(false) {}
4196 
4197  PotentialValuesState(bool IsValid)
4198  : IsValidState(IsValid), UndefIsContained(false) {}
4199 
4200  /// See AbstractState::isValidState(...)
4201  bool isValidState() const override { return IsValidState.isValidState(); }
4202 
4203  /// See AbstractState::isAtFixpoint(...)
4204  bool isAtFixpoint() const override { return IsValidState.isAtFixpoint(); }
4205 
4206  /// See AbstractState::indicatePessimisticFixpoint(...)
4207  ChangeStatus indicatePessimisticFixpoint() override {
4208  return IsValidState.indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4209  }
4210 
4211  /// See AbstractState::indicateOptimisticFixpoint(...)
4212  ChangeStatus indicateOptimisticFixpoint() override {
4213  return IsValidState.indicateOptimisticFixpoint();
4214  }
4215 
4216  /// Return the assumed state
4217  PotentialValuesState &getAssumed() { return *this; }
4218  const PotentialValuesState &getAssumed() const { return *this; }
4219 
4220  /// Return this set. We should check whether this set is valid or not by
4221  /// isValidState() before calling this function.
4222  const SetTy &getAssumedSet() const {
4223  assert(isValidState() && "This set shoud not be used when it is invalid!");
4224  return Set;
4225  }
4226 
4227  /// Returns whether this state contains an undef value or not.
4228  bool undefIsContained() const {
4229  assert(isValidState() && "This flag shoud not be used when it is invalid!");
4230  return UndefIsContained;
4231  }
4232 
4233  bool operator==(const PotentialValuesState &RHS) const {
4234  if (isValidState() != RHS.isValidState())
4235  return false;
4236  if (!isValidState() && !RHS.isValidState())
4237  return true;
4238  if (undefIsContained() != RHS.undefIsContained())
4239  return false;
4240  return Set == RHS.getAssumedSet();
4241  }
4242 
4243  /// Maximum number of potential values to be tracked.
4244  /// This is set by -attributor-max-potential-values command line option
4245  static unsigned MaxPotentialValues;
4246 
4247  /// Return empty set as the best state of potential values.
4248  static PotentialValuesState getBestState() {
4249  return PotentialValuesState(true);
4250  }
4251 
4252  static PotentialValuesState getBestState(PotentialValuesState &PVS) {
4253  return getBestState();
4254  }
4255 
4256  /// Return full set as the worst state of potential values.
4257  static PotentialValuesState getWorstState() {
4258  return PotentialValuesState(false);
4259  }
4260 
4261  /// Union assumed set with the passed value.
4262  void unionAssumed(const MemberTy &C) { insert(C); }
4263 
4264  /// Union assumed set with assumed set of the passed state \p PVS.
4265  void unionAssumed(const PotentialValuesState &PVS) { unionWith(PVS); }
4266 
4267  /// Union assumed set with an undef value.
4268  void unionAssumedWithUndef() { unionWithUndef(); }
4269 
4270  /// "Clamp" this state with \p PVS.
4271  PotentialValuesState operator^=(const PotentialValuesState &PVS) {
4272  IsValidState ^= PVS.IsValidState;
4273  unionAssumed(PVS);
4274  return *this;
4275  }
4276 
4277  PotentialValuesState operator&=(const PotentialValuesState &PVS) {
4278  IsValidState &= PVS.IsValidState;
4279  unionAssumed(PVS);
4280  return *this;
4281  }
4282 
4283 private:
4284  /// Check the size of this set, and invalidate when the size is no
4285  /// less than \p MaxPotentialValues threshold.
4286  void checkAndInvalidate() {
4287  if (Set.size() >= MaxPotentialValues)
4288  indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4289  else
4290  reduceUndefValue();
4291  }
4292 
4293  /// If this state contains both undef and not undef, we can reduce
4294  /// undef to the not undef value.
4295  void reduceUndefValue() { UndefIsContained = UndefIsContained & Set.empty(); }
4296 
4297  /// Insert an element into this set.
4298  void insert(const MemberTy &C) {
4299  if (!isValidState())
4300  return;
4301  Set.insert(C);
4302  checkAndInvalidate();
4303  }
4304 
4305  /// Take union with R.
4306  void unionWith(const PotentialValuesState &R) {
4307  /// If this is a full set, do nothing.
4308  if (!isValidState())
4309  return;
4310  /// If R is full set, change L to a full set.
4311  if (!R.isValidState()) {
4312  indicatePessimisticFixpoint();
4313  return;
4314  }
4315  for (const MemberTy &C : R.Set)
4316  Set.insert(C);
4317  UndefIsContained |= R.undefIsContained();
4318  checkAndInvalidate();
4319  }
4320 
4321  /// Take union with an undef value.
4322  void unionWithUndef() {
4323  UndefIsContained = true;
4324  reduceUndefValue();
4325  }
4326 
4327  /// Take intersection with R.
4328  void intersectWith(const PotentialValuesState &R) {
4329  /// If R is a full set, do nothing.
4330  if (!R.isValidState())
4331  return;
4332  /// If this is a full set, change this to R.
4333  if (!isValidState()) {
4334  *this = R;
4335  return;
4336  }
4337  SetTy IntersectSet;
4338  for (const MemberTy &C : Set) {
4339  if (R.Set.count(C))
4340  IntersectSet.insert(C);
4341  }
4342  Set = IntersectSet;
4343  UndefIsContained &= R.undefIsContained();
4344  reduceUndefValue();
4345  }
4346 
4347  /// A helper state which indicate whether this state is valid or not.
4348  BooleanState IsValidState;
4349 
4350  /// Container for potential values
4351  SetTy Set;
4352 
4353  /// Flag for undef value
4354  bool UndefIsContained;
4355 };
4356 
4357 using PotentialConstantIntValuesState = PotentialValuesState<APInt>;
4358 
4359 raw_ostream &operator<<(raw_ostream &OS,
4360  const PotentialConstantIntValuesState &R);
4361 
4362 /// An abstract interface for potential values analysis.
4363 ///
4364 /// This AA collects potential values for each IR position.
4365 /// An assumed set of potential values is initialized with the empty set (the
4366 /// best state) and it will grow monotonically as we find more potential values
4367 /// for this position.
4368 /// The set might be forced to the worst state, that is, to contain every
4369 /// possible value for this position in 2 cases.
4370 /// 1. We surpassed the \p MaxPotentialValues threshold. This includes the
4371 /// case that this position is affected (e.g. because of an operation) by a
4372 /// Value that is in the worst state.
4373 /// 2. We tried to initialize on a Value that we cannot handle (e.g. an
4374 /// operator we do not currently handle).
4375 ///
4376 /// TODO: Support values other than constant integers.
4377 struct AAPotentialValues
4378  : public StateWrapper<PotentialConstantIntValuesState, AbstractAttribute> {
4379  using Base = StateWrapper<PotentialConstantIntValuesState, AbstractAttribute>;
4380  AAPotentialValues(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A) : Base(IRP) {}
4381 
4382  /// See AbstractAttribute::getState(...).
4383  PotentialConstantIntValuesState &getState() override { return *this; }
4384  const PotentialConstantIntValuesState &getState() const override {
4385  return *this;
4386  }
4387 
4388  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4389  static AAPotentialValues &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4390  Attributor &A);
4391 
4392  /// Return assumed constant for the associated value
4393  Optional<ConstantInt *>
4394  getAssumedConstantInt(Attributor &A,
4395  const Instruction *CtxI = nullptr) const {
4396  if (!isValidState())
4397  return nullptr;
4398  if (getAssumedSet().size() == 1)
4399  return cast<ConstantInt>(ConstantInt::get(getAssociatedValue().getType(),
4400  *(getAssumedSet().begin())));
4401  if (getAssumedSet().size() == 0) {
4402  if (undefIsContained())
4403  return cast<ConstantInt>(
4404  ConstantInt::get(getAssociatedValue().getType(), 0));
4405  return llvm::None;
4406  }
4407 
4408  return nullptr;
4409  }
4410 
4411  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4412  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAPotentialValues"; }
4413 
4414  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4415  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4416 
4417  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4418  /// AAPotentialValues
4419  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4420  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4421  }
4422 
4423  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4424  static const char ID;
4425 };

4429  : public IRAttribute<Attribute::NoUndef,
4430  StateWrapper<BooleanState, AbstractAttribute>> {

4433  /// Return true if we assume that the underlying value is noundef.

4437  bool isKnownNoUndef() const { return getKnown(); }
4438 
4439  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4440  static AANoUndef &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A);
4441 
4442  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()

4444

4694 /// An abstract interface for struct information.
4695 struct AAPointerInfo : public AbstractAttribute {
4696  AAPointerInfo(const IRPosition &IRP) : AbstractAttribute(IRP) {}
4697 
4698  enum AccessKind {
4699  AK_READ = 1 << 0,
4700  AK_WRITE = 1 << 1,
4701  AK_READ_WRITE = AK_READ | AK_WRITE,
4702  };
4703 
4704  /// An access description.
4705  struct Access {
4706  Access(Instruction *I, Optional<Value *> Content, AccessKind Kind, Type *Ty)
4707  : LocalI(I), RemoteI(I), Content(Content), Kind(Kind), Ty(Ty) {}
4708  Access(Instruction *LocalI, Instruction *RemoteI, Optional<Value *> Content,
4709  AccessKind Kind, Type *Ty)
4710  : LocalI(LocalI), RemoteI(RemoteI), Content(Content), Kind(Kind),
4711  Ty(Ty) {}
4712  Access(const Access &Other) = default;
4713  Access(const Access &&Other)
4714  : LocalI(Other.LocalI), RemoteI(Other.RemoteI), Content(Other.Content),
4715  Kind(Other.Kind), Ty(Other.Ty) {}
4716 
4717  Access &operator=(const Access &Other) = default;
4718  bool operator==(const Access &R) const {
4719  return LocalI == R.LocalI && RemoteI == R.RemoteI &&
4720  Content == R.Content && Kind == R.Kind;
4721  }
4722  bool operator!=(const Access &R) const { return !(*this == R); }
4723 
4724  Access &operator&=(const Access &R) {
4725  assert(RemoteI == R.RemoteI && "Expected same instruction!");
4726  Content =
4727  AA::combineOptionalValuesInAAValueLatice(Content, R.Content, Ty);
4728  Kind = AccessKind(Kind | R.Kind);
4729  return *this;
4730  }
4731 
4732  /// Return the access kind.
4733  AccessKind getKind() const { return Kind; }
4734 
4735  /// Return true if this is a read access.
4736  bool isRead() const { return Kind & AK_READ; }
4737 
4738  /// Return true if this is a write access.
4739  bool isWrite() const { return Kind & AK_WRITE; }
4740 
4741  /// Return the instruction that causes the access with respect to the local
4742  /// scope of the associated attribute.
4743  Instruction *getLocalInst() const { return LocalI; }
4744 
4745  /// Return the actual instruction that causes the access.
4746  Instruction *getRemoteInst() const { return RemoteI; }
4747 
4748  /// Return true if the value written is not known yet.
4749  bool isWrittenValueYetUndetermined() const { return !Content.hasValue(); }
4750 
4751  /// Return true if the value written cannot be determined at all.
4752  bool isWrittenValueUnknown() const {
4753  return Content.hasValue() && !*Content;
4754  }
4755 
4756  /// Return the type associated with the access, if known.
4757  Type *getType() const { return Ty; }
4758 
4759  /// Return the value writen, if any. As long as
4760  /// isWrittenValueYetUndetermined return true this function shall not be
4761  /// called.
4762  Value *getWrittenValue() const { return *Content; }
4763 
4764  /// Return the written value which can be `llvm::null` if it is not yet
4765  /// determined.
4766  Optional<Value *> getContent() const { return Content; }
4767 
4768  private:
4769  /// The instruction responsible for the access with respect to the local
4770  /// scope of the associated attribute.
4771  Instruction *LocalI;
4772 
4773  /// The instruction responsible for the access.
4774  Instruction *RemoteI;
4775 
4776  /// The value written, if any. `llvm::none` means "not known yet", `nullptr`
4777  /// cannot be determined.
4778  Optional<Value *> Content;
4779 
4780  /// The access kind, e.g., READ, as bitset (could be more than one).
4781  AccessKind Kind;
4782 
4783  /// The type of the content, thus the type read/written, can be null if not
4784  /// available.
4785  Type *Ty;
4786  };
4787 
4788  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4789  static AAPointerInfo &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A);
4790 
4791  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4792  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAPointerInfo"; }
4793 
4794  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4795  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4796 
4797  /// Call \p CB on all accesses that might interfere with \p LI and return true
4798  /// if all such accesses were known and the callback returned true for all of
4799  /// them, false otherwise.
4800  virtual bool forallInterferingAccesses(
4801  LoadInst &LI, function_ref<bool(const Access &, bool)> CB) const = 0;
4802  virtual bool forallInterferingAccesses(
4803  StoreInst &SI, function_ref<bool(const Access &, bool)> CB) const = 0;
4804 
4805  /// Call \p CB on all write accesses that might interfere with \p LI and
4806  /// return true if all such accesses were known and the callback returned true
4807  /// for all of them, false otherwise. In contrast to forallInterferingAccesses
4808  /// this function will perform reasoning to exclude write accesses that cannot
4809  /// affect the load even if they on the surface look as if they would.
4810  virtual bool forallInterferingWrites(
4811  Attributor &A, const AbstractAttribute &QueryingAA, LoadInst &LI,
4812  function_ref<bool(const Access &, bool)> CB) const = 0;
4813 
4814  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is AAPointerInfo
4815  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4816  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4817  }
4818 
4819  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4820  static const char ID;
4821 };
4822 
4823 /// An abstract attribute for getting assumption information.
4824 struct AAAssumptionInfo
4825  : public StateWrapper<SetState<StringRef>, AbstractAttribute,
4826  DenseSet<StringRef>> {
4827  using Base =
4828  StateWrapper<SetState<StringRef>, AbstractAttribute, DenseSet<StringRef>>;
4829 
4830  AAAssumptionInfo(const IRPosition &IRP, Attributor &A,
4831  const DenseSet<StringRef> &Known)
4832  : Base(IRP, Known) {}
4833 
4834  /// Returns true if the assumption set contains the assumption \p Assumption.
4835  virtual bool hasAssumption(const StringRef Assumption) const = 0;
4836 
4837  /// Create an abstract attribute view for the position \p IRP.
4838  static AAAssumptionInfo &createForPosition(const IRPosition &IRP,
4839  Attributor &A);
4840 
4841  /// See AbstractAttribute::getName()
4842  const std::string getName() const override { return "AAAssumptionInfo"; }
4843 
4844  /// See AbstractAttribute::getIdAddr()
4845  const char *getIdAddr() const override { return &ID; }
4846 
4847  /// This function should return true if the type of the \p AA is
4848  /// AAAssumptionInfo
4849  static bool classof(const AbstractAttribute *AA) {
4850  return (AA->getIdAddr() == &ID);
4851  }
4852 
4853  /// Unique ID (due to the unique address)
4854  static const char ID;
4855 };
